vided (TV series)|A House Divided]]''\n|Carissa Walker\n|Series regular\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[American Soul]]''\n| [[June Pointer]]\n| Upcoming; guest appearance\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Motherland: Fort Salem]]''\n| Anacostia<ref>{{cite web |url=https://tvline.com/2019/03/05/freeform-military-witch-drama-series-motherland-fort-salem-video/ |title=Freeform Orders Drama Series About Witches in the Military \u2014 Watch Teaser |work=[[TVLine]] |first=Andy |last=Swift |date=March 5, 2019 |accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref>\n| Series regular\n|}\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Studio albums ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:12em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:19em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"1\"| Peak positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Independent Albums|US<br>Indie]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/music/demetria-mckinney/chart-history/independent-albums|title=Demetria McKinney Chart History|publisher=|accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref><br>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Officially Yours''\n|\n* Released: October 6, 2017<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/gp/aw/d/B00WVMMKS0/ref=zg_bsnr_67186_29?ie=UTF8&psc=1&refRID=DG8X5BDAG2SY1JP8CZ6J|title=Officially Yours|date=6 October 2017|publisher=|accessdate=14 November 2017|via=Amazon}}</ref>\n* Label: [[EOne Entertainment|Entertainment One Music]] \n* Formats: [[Compact Disc|CD]], [[Music download|digital download]]\n| 48\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Singles ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"|Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\"|Peak chart position\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"|Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\" | [[Billboard Hot 100|US]]<br>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"|[[Adult R&B Songs|US <br/>Adult R&B]]<br><ref name=\"USR&B\">{{cite web|title=demetria  Album & Song Chart History: R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/6582155/demetria-mckinney/chart|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=August 29, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Get Yo ..Ish\"\n| 2011\n| \u2014 || \u2014\n| rowspan=\"7\" {{n/a}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Take Away This Love\"\n| 2012\n| \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Still Believe in Love (feat. [[Musiq Soulchild]])\" \n| rowspan=\"2\"|2013\n| \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| \"Work With Me\"\n| \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"100 (feat. [[da Brat]])\" \n| 2015\n| \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Trade It All\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2015\n| \u2014 || 25\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Unnecessary Trouble]] (feat. [[Kandi Burruss]])\"\n| \u2014 || \u2014\n|-  \n! scope=\"row\"| \"Easy\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2017\n| \u2014 || 4\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''Officially Yours''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Is This Love\"\n| \u2014 || \u2014\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official website|http://www.demetriamckinney.com/home/}}\n* {{IMDb name|2351246}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McKinney, Demetria}}\n[[Category:African-American actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:American people of Filipino descent]]\n[[Category:Filipino emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American actresses of Filipino descent]]\n[[Category:African-American female models]]\n[[Category:Female models from New Mexico]]\n[[Category:African-American models]]\n[[Category:African-American female singers]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Albuquerque, New Mexico]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n", "name_user": "Vattav", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Demetria_McKinney"}
{"title_page": "Basilica della Santa Casa", "text_new": "{{about|a church in Loreto, Italy|a church in [[Prague]]|Loreta|a chapel in [[Santa Fe, New Mexico]]|Loretto Chapel}}\n{{Infobox church\n| denomination = [[Catholic Church]]\n| name = Basilica della Santa Casa\n| image = Basilica Pontificia della Santa Casa di Loreto.jpg\n| caption = The fa\u00e7ade edifice of the Basilica della Santa Casa.\n| location = [[Loreto, Marche]], Italy\n| status = [[Pontifical minor basilica|Pontifical]] [[minor basilica]]\n| style = [[Gothic architecture|Late Gothic]]\n| year completed = 16th century\n| episcopalarea = [[Roman Catholic Territorial Prelature of Loreto|Territorial Prelature of Loreto]]\n}}\nThe '''Basilica della Santa Casa''' ({{lang-en|Basilica of the Holy House}}) is a shrine of Marian [[pilgrimage]] in [[Loreto (AN)|Loreto]], [[Italy]]. The basilica  is known for enshrining  the house in which the [[Blessed Virgin Mary]] is believed by some Catholics to have lived. A legend claims the same house was flown over by [[angel]]ic beings from [[Nazareth]] to [[Tersatto]] (Trsat in [[Croatia]]), then to [[Recanati]], before arriving at the current site.<ref>Donald Posner - Annibale Carracci, A study in the reform of Italian painting, 1971. The painting was originally in the basilica of the Santa Casa in Loreto.</ref><ref>History of Italian Renaissance Art: Painting, Sculpture, Architecture  Frederick Hartt, David G. Wilkins - 2010 \"Sixtus's nephews who appears in the group portrait, called Melozzo to Loreto, on the Adriatic coast, to decorate the sacristy of the basilica of the Santa Casa (fig. 14.26). \"</ref>{{dubious|Both \"sources\" are rather comments, and apparently unrelated - seem to refer to the Black Madonna, which hasn't even been mentioned yet. Chaos!|date=March 2020}}\n\n[[Pope Benedict XV]] designated the Blessed Virgin Mary under the same title to be Patroness of air passengers and auspicious travel on 24&nbsp;March 1920. Accordingly, [[Pope Pius XI]] granted a [[Canonical Coronation]] to the image of Our Lady of Loreto made of [[Cedar of Lebanon]] on 5&nbsp;September 1922, replacing the torched image consumed in fire on 23 February 1921.{{dubious|WHAT is the subject here? The Black Madonna? Say so! Is it a painting or a statue? How is it connected to the house? Total chaos!|date=March 2020}}\n\n=={{anchor|Basilica of the Holy House}}The church building==\n<!-- This Anchor tag serves to provide a permanent target for incoming section links. Please do not move it out of the section heading, even though it disrupts edit summary generation (you can manually fix the edit summary before you save your changes). Please do not modify it, even if you modify the section title. It is always best to anchor an old section header that has been changed so that links to it won't be broken. See [[Template:Anchor]] for details. (This text: [[Template:Anchor comment]]) -->\nThe basilica is a [[Gothic architecture|Late Gothic]] structure continued by [[Giuliano da Maiano]] (1432\u20131490), [[Giuliano da Sangallo]] (1445\u20131516) and [[Donato Bramante]] (1444\u20131514).<ref name=fodors>[http://www.fodors.com/world/europe/italy/umbria-and-the-marches/review-160757.html \"Basilica della Santa Casa\", Fodor's] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141029171741/http://www.fodors.com/world/europe/italy/umbria-and-the-marches/review-160757.html |date=October 29, 2014 }}</ref> It is 93 meters long, 60 meters wide, and its campanile is 75.6 meters high.\n\nThe [[fa\u00e7ade]] of the church was erected under [[Pope Sixtus V|Sixtus&nbsp;V]], who in 1586 fortified Loreto and gave it the privileges of a town; his colossal statue stands on the [[parvis]], above the front steps, a third of the way to the left as one enters. Over the principal doorway there is a lifesize bronze statue of the Virgin and Child by [[Girolamo Lombardo]]; the three superb bronze doors executed at the latter end of the 16th century under the reign of [[Pope Paul V|Paul V]] (1605\u20131621) are also by Lombardo (1506-1590), his sons and his pupils, among them [[Tiburzio Vergelli]] (1551-1609), who also made the fine bronze [[baptismal font|font]] in the interior. The doors and hanging lamps are by the same artists.<ref name=fodors/>\n\nThe richly decorated [[campanile]] (1750 to 1754), by [[Luigi Vanvitelli]],<ref name=fodors/> is of great height; the principal bell, presented by [[Pope Leo X|Leo X]] in 1516, weighs 11 tons.\n\nThe interior of the church has [[mosaic]]s by [[Domenichino]] and [[Guido Reni]] and other works of art, including statues by [[Raffaello da Montelupo]]. In the [[Sacristy|sacristies]] on each side of the right [[transept]] are [[fresco]]es, on the right by [[Melozzo da Forl\u00ec]], on the left by [[Luca Signorelli]] and in both there are some fine [[intarsia]]s; the basilica as a whole is thus a collaborative work by generations of architects and artists.\n\n==The ''Santa Casa''==\n[[File:Santuario della Santa Casa in Loreto - Casa Santa.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Marble screen around the Holy House]]\n\nThe main attraction of Loreto is the Holy House itself (in [[Italian language|Italian]], the ''Santa Casa di Loreto''). It has been a [[Catholic]] pilgrimage destination since at least the 14th century and a popular tourist destination for non-Catholics as well.\n\n===Description===\n====The \"house\"====\nThe \"house\" itself is a plain stone building, 8.5&nbsp;m  by 3.8 m  and 4.1 m  high; it has a door on the north side and a window on the west. A niche contains a small [[black Madonna|black image of the Virgin and Child]], a statue in [[Lebanon cedar]], richly adorned with jewels (for more see [[Basilica della Santa Casa#Our Lady of Loreto|below]]).\n\n====The sculpted marble screen====\nAround the house is a tall marble screen designed by Bramante and executed under Popes Leo&nbsp;X, [[Pope Clement VII|Clement VII]] and [[Pope Paul III|Paul III]], by [[Andrea Sansovino]], Girolamo Lombardo, [[Bartolommeo Bandinelli|Bandinelli]], [[Guglielmo della Porta]] and others in the [[baroque]] style. The four sides represent the [[Annunciation]], the [[Nativity of Jesus in art|Nativity]], the Arrival of the Santa Casa at Loreto and the [[Nativity of the Blessed Virgin Mary|Nativity of the Virgin]], respectively.\n\n===The treasury===\nThe treasury contains a large variety of rich and curious votive offerings. The architectural design is finer than the details of the sculpture. The apse is decorated with 19th-century German frescoes.\n\n==Tradition==\n[[File:Loreto Fresko.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Fresco by [[Melozzo da Forl\u00ec]] in the sacristy of St Marc]]\n\nThe town has been a popular pilgrimage site{{for what|date=April 2020}} since the 13th century.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n===In Nazareth===\nLate medieval religious traditions developed suggesting that this was the house in which the [[Holy Family]] (Mary, Joseph and Jesus) had lived while in [[Judea (Roman province)|Judea]] at the start of the first century AD, and which was miraculously flown over to Europe by four angels just before the final expulsion of the Christian [[Crusaders]] from the [[Holy Land]], in order to protect it from [[Muslim]] soldiers. According to this narrative, the house at [[Nazareth]] in which [[Mary, the mother of Jesus|Mary]] had been born and brought up, potentially received the [[Annunciation]], and had lived during the childhood of Christ{{dubious|Is it really part of the legend? A married woman moved to her husband's house.|date=April 2020}} and after his [[Ascension of Jesus Christ|Ascension]], and was converted into a church by the [[Twelve Apostles]].{{dubious|Poor use of punctuation. Is it meant to say that she lived in the house after the Ascension, or that the Apostles made it into a church  after the Ascension? If the former, we do have different, strong post-Ascension traditions placing Mary in Jerusalem and Ephesus, NOT Nazareth.|date=April 2020}}{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn 336, [[Helena (Empress)|Empress Helena]] made a pilgrimage to Nazareth and allegedly directed that a basilica be erected over it, in which worship continued until the fall of the Crusader [[Kingdom of Jerusalem]]. However, there is no firm historical evidence that Helena did in fact make such a intervention.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n===To Dalmatia and Italy===\nThe tale further states that, threatened with destruction by Muslim soldiers, the house was miraculously carried by [[angel]]s through the air and initially deposited in 1291 on a hill at [[Tersatto]] (now Trsat, a suburb of [[Rijeka]], [[Croatia]]), where an appearance of the Virgin and numerous [[miracle|miraculous]] cures attested to its sanctity. The miraculous translation of the house is said to have been confirmed by investigations made at Nazareth by messengers from the governor of [[Dalmatia]]. In 1294, angels again carried it across the [[Adriatic Sea]] to the woods near [[Recanati]] (although the reasoning is not clear as to why this happened); from these woods (Latin ''lauretum'', Italian ''Colle dei Lauri'' or from the name of its proprietress Laureta) the chapel derived the name which it still retains (Lat. ''sacellum glorios\u00e6 Virginis in Laureto''). From this spot it was afterwards removed to the present hill in 1295, with a slight adjustment being required to fix it in its current site. It is this house that gave rise to the title ''Our Lady of Loreto'', sometimes applied to the Virgin; the miracle is occasionally represented in religious art wherein the house is borne by an angelic host.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Papal support===\n[[papal bull|Bulls]] in favour of the Shrine at Loreto were issued by [[Pope Sixtus IV|Pope Sixtus IV]] in 1491 (although, since Sixtus IV died in 1484, either the date is erroneous, or else the pope should be Innocent VIII), and by [[Pope Julius II|Julius II]] in 1507, the last alluding to the translation of the house with some caution (''ut pie creditur et fama est''). While, like most miracles, the translation of the house is not a matter of faith for Catholics, nonetheless, in the late 17th century, [[Pope Innocent XII|Innocent XII]] appointed a ''missa cum officio proprio'' (a special [[mass]]) for the Feast of the Translation of the Holy House, which as late as the 20th century was enjoined in the [[Spanish Breviary]] as a [[Ranking of liturgical days in the Roman Rite#History|greater double]] on December 10. This mass was recently restored by Pope Francis in 2019.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nOn 4 October 2012, [[Benedict XVI]] visited the Shrine to mark the 50th anniversary of [[John XXIII]]'s visit. In his visit, Benedict formally entrusted the [[World Synod of Bishops]] and the Year of Faith to the Virgin of Loreto.<ref name=cns>{{cite news |title= Pope at Marian shrine entrusts Year of Faith, synod to Mary |url= http://www.catholicnews.com/data/stories/cns/1204169.htm |archive-url= http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121205203916/http://www.catholicnews.com/data/stories/cns/1204169.htm |url-status= dead |archive-date=5 December 2012 |access-date=18 December 2012 |newspaper= Catholic News Service |date=4 October 2012 }}</ref><ref>[https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/benedict_xvi/homilies/2012/documents/hf_ben-xvi_hom_20121004_loreto_en.html Pastoral visit of Benedict XVI to Loreto] {{webarchive |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130102054537/https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/benedict_xvi/homilies/2012/documents/hf_ben-xvi_hom_20121004_loreto_en.html |date=2 January 2013 }}</ref><ref>[https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/benedict_xvi/prayers/documents/hf_ben-xvi_20070901_prayer-loreto_en.html Benedict XVI, Prayer to Our Lady of Loreto] {{webarchive |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130102120718/https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/benedict_xvi/prayers/documents/hf_ben-xvi_20070901_prayer-loreto_en.html |date= January 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Historicity==\nThe documented history of the house can only be traced as far back as the close of the [[Crusades]], around the 14th century. An early brief reference is made in the ''Italia Illustrata'' of [[Flavius Blondus]] (1392\u20131463), secretary to Popes [[Pope Eugene IV|Eugene&nbsp;IV]], [[Pope Nicholas V|Nicholas V]], [[Pope Calixtus III|Calixtus III]] and [[Pope Pius II|Pius II]]; it can be read in its entirety in the ''Redemptoris mundi Matris Ecclesi\u00e6 Lauretana historia'', by a certain Teremannus, contained in the ''Opera Omnia'' (1576) of [[Mantuanus|Baptista Mantuanus]].\n\n==History==\nAccording to [[Herbert Thurston]], in some respects the Lauretan tradition is \"beset with difficulties of the gravest kind\", which were noted in a 1906 work on the subject. There are documents which indicate that a church dedicated to the Blessed Virgin already existed at Loreto in the twelfth and thirteenth centuries, that is, 180 years before the time of the supposed translation; and there is no mention of the supposed miraculous translation of the Holy House in 1472. Thurston notes that papal confirmations of the Loreto tradition are relatively late (the first Bull mentioning the translation is that of Julius II in 1507), but that they are at first very guarded in expression, for Julius introduces the clause \"''ut pie creditur et fama est''\", \"as is piously believed and reported to be\".<ref name=Thurston>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/13454b.htm Thurston, Herbert. \"Santa Casa di Loreto.\" The Catholic Encyclopedia] Vol. 13. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1912. 10 December 2017</ref> Thurston suggests that a miracle-working statue or picture of the Madonna was brought from Tersato in [[Illyria]] to Loreto by some pious Christians and was then confounded with the ancient rustic chapel in which it was harboured, the veneration formerly given to the statue afterwards passing to the building.<ref name=Thurston/>\n\nFinally, he draws comparisons to the shrine at [[Our Lady of Walsingham|Walsingham]], the principal English shrine of the Blessed Virgin, the legend of \"Our Lady's house\" (written down about 1465, and consequently earlier than the Loreto translation tradition) supposes that in the time of St. Edward the Confessor a chapel was built at Walsingham, which exactly reproduced the dimensions of the Holy House of Nazareth. When the carpenters could not complete it upon the site that had been chosen, it was transferred and erected by angels' hands at a spot two hundred feet away.<ref>\"The Month\", September 1901</ref>\n\nIn modern times, the Church traced the linguistic origins of the story to a local aristocratic family called \"Angelos\", which were responsible for the transfer.<ref name=kerr>{{cite news|last=Kerr|first=David|title=Pope entrusts Year of Faith, evangelization synod to Mary|url=http://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/pope-entrusts-year-of-faith-evangelization-synod-to-mary/|accessdate=18 December 2012|newspaper=Catholic News Agency|date=4 October 2012}}</ref> According to Papal archivist Giuseppe Lapponi, it seems that a family by the name of Angeli saved the bricks of the Holy House from the Muslim invasion. Excavations beneath the House of Loreto found coins, two of which are connected to the Angeli family.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://udayton.edu/imri/mary/o/our-lady-of-loreto-and-aviation.php |title=Roten SM, Johann. \"Our Lady of Loreto and Aviation\", International Marian Research Institute, University of Dayton |publisher=Udayton.edu |date=1920-03-24 |accessdate=2020-01-19}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Our Lady of Loreto.jpg|thumb|The venerated Marian image of ''Our Lady of Loreto''. The cedar wood was timbered from the [[Vatican Gardens]].]]\n\n==Our Lady of Loreto==\n'''Our Lady of Loreto''' is the title of the Virgin Mary with respect to the Holy House of Loreto. Her statue, carved from Cedar of Lebanon, is a \"[[Black Madonna]],\" owing to centuries of lamp smoke.{{dubious|Maybe the original one, but this one's from 1922. Chaos!|date=March 2020}} It, like the Holy House, is associated with miracles. In the 1600s a Mass and a Marian litany was approved. This \"Litany of Loreto\" is the [[Litany of the Blessed Virgin Mary]], one of the five litanies approved for public recitation by the Church. In 1920 [[Pope Benedict XV]] declared the Madonna of Loreto [[patron saint]] of air travellers and pilots.<ref>[http://www.ewtn.com/v/experts/showmessage.asp?number=444755 Donovan, Colin B., \"Our Lady of Loreto\", EWTN, August 2, 2005]{{dead link|date=January 2020}}</ref> The statue was commissioned after a fire in the Santa Casa in 1921 destroyed the original madonna, and it was granted a [[Canonical Coronation]] in 1922 by [[Pope Pius XI]]. In October 2019 [[Pope Francis]] restored the feast of Our Lady of Loreto, commemorated on December 10, to the universal Roman calendar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://catholicnewsherald.com/news/world/93-news/vatican/5082-pope-adds-feast-of-our-lady-of-loreto-to-universal-calendar |title=Pope adds feast of Our Lady of Loreto to universal calendar |publisher=Catholicnewsherald.com |date=2019-10-31 |accessdate=2020-01-19}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|Santuario della Santa Casa (Loreto)}}\n\n* [[Basilica of the Annunciation]] in Nazareth\n* [[House of the Virgin Mary]]\n* [[Giovanni Tonucci]]\n* [[Territorial prelature of Loreto]]\n* [[Church of Our Lady of Loreto|Loreto Church]] in [[Warsaw]]\n* [[Loreta]] in [[Prague]]\n* [[Our Lady of Loreto and St Winefride's, Kew]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last=Grimaldi|first=Floriano |title=La Chiesa di Santa Maria di Loreto nei documenti dei secoli XII - XV|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cg6lugEACAAJ|year=1984|publisher=Stabilimento Tipografico Mierma|location=Ancona|language=Italian, Latin}}\n*{{cite book|last=Grimaldi|first=Floriano |title=La historia della Chiesa di Santa Maria de Loreto|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a92KEzlvzdIC|year=1993|publisher=Carilo|location=Loreto|language=Italian}}\n*{{cite book|last=Hutchison|first=William Antony|title=Loreto and Nazareth: Two Lectures, Containing the Results of Personal Investigation of the Two Sanctuaries|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4yBDgxav7dYC&pg=PP13|year=1863|publisher=E. Dillon|location=London}}\n*{{cite book|last=Leopardi|first=Monaldo|title=La Santa Casa di Loreto: discussioni istoriche e critiche|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dvsdUdTijGoC&pg=PA1|year=1841|publisher=presso Francesco Veladini e C.|location=Lugano|language=Italian}}\n*{{cite book|first=Karin|last=V\u00e9lez|title=The Miraculous Flying House of Loreto: Spreading Catholicism in the Early Modern World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VT5hDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA127|year=2018|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0-691-18449-4}}\n\n::{{catholic|title=Santa Casa di Loreto}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.santuarioloreto.it/default_eng.htm Sanctuary of Loreto] - Official site\n{{portal bar|Architecture|Catholicism|Italy}}\n{{coord|43.44095|N|13.610578|E|source:itwiki_region:IT|format=dms|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Holy See}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Basilica Della Santa Casa}}\n[[Category:Basilica churches in the Marche|Casa Santa]]\n[[Category:Catholic pilgrimage sites]]\n[[Category:Marian shrines]]\n[[Category:Properties of the Holy See]]\n[[Category:Loreto, Marche]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|a church in Loreto, Italy|a church in [[Prague]]|Loreta|a chapel in [[Santa Fe, New Mexico]]|Loretto Chapel}}\n{{Infobox church\n| denomination = [[Catholic Church]]\n| name = Basilica della Santa Casa\n| image = Basilica Pontificia della Santa Casa di Loreto.jpg\n| caption = The fa\u00e7ade edifice of the Basilica della Santa Casa.\n| location = [[Loreto, Marche]], Italy\n| status = [[Pontifical minor basilica|Pontifical]] [[minor basilica]]\n| style = [[Gothic architecture|Late Gothic]]\n| year completed = 16th century\n| episcopalarea = [[Roman Catholic Territorial Prelature of Loreto|Territorial Prelature of Loreto]]\n}}\nThe '''Basilica della Santa Casa''' ({{lang-en|Basilica of the Holy House}}) is a shrine of Marian [[pilgrimage]] in [[Loreto (AN)|Loreto]], [[Italy]]. The basilica  is known for enshrining  the house in which the [[Blessed Virgin Mary]] is believed by some Catholics to have lived. A legend claims the same house was flown over by [[angel]]ic beings from [[Nazareth]] to [[Tersatto]] (Trsat in [[Croatia]]), then to [[Recanati]], before arriving at the current site.<ref>Donald Posner - Annibale Carracci, A study in the reform of Italian painting, 1971. The painting was originally in the basilica of the Santa Casa in Loreto.</ref><ref>History of Italian Renaissance Art: Painting, Sculpture, Architecture  Frederick Hartt, David G. Wilkins - 2010 \"Sixtus's nephews who appears in the group portrait, called Melozzo to Loreto, on the Adriatic coast, to decorate the sacristy of the basilica of the Santa Casa (fig. 14.26). \"</ref>{{dubious|Both \"sources\" are rather comments, and apparently unrelated - seem to refer to the Black Madonna, which hasn't even been mentioned yet. Chaos!|date=March 2020}}\n\n[[Pope Benedict XV]] designated the Blessed Virgin Mary under the same title to be Patroness of air passengers and auspicious travel on 24&nbsp;March 1920. Accordingly, [[Pope Pius XI]] granted a [[Canonical Coronation]] to the image of Our Lady of Loreto made of [[Cedar of Lebanon]] on 5&nbsp;September 1922, replacing the torched image consumed in fire on 23 February 1921.{{dubious|WHAT is the subject here? The Black Madonna? Say so! Is it a painting or a statue? How is it connected to the house? Total chaos!|date=March 2020}}\n\n=={{anchor|Basilica of the Holy House}}The church building==\n<!-- This Anchor tag serves to provide a permanent target for incoming section links. Please do not move it out of the section heading, even though it disrupts edit summary generation (you can manually fix the edit summary before you save your changes). Please do not modify it, even if you modify the section title. It is always best to anchor an old section header that has been changed so that links to it won't be broken. See [[Template:Anchor]] for details. (This text: [[Template:Anchor comment]]) -->\nThe basilica is a [[Gothic architecture|Late Gothic]] structure continued by [[Giuliano da Maiano]] (1432\u20131490), [[Giuliano da Sangallo]] (1445\u20131516) and [[Donato Bramante]] (1444\u20131514).<ref name=fodors>[http://www.fodors.com/world/europe/italy/umbria-and-the-marches/review-160757.html \"Basilica della Santa Casa\", Fodor's] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141029171741/http://www.fodors.com/world/europe/italy/umbria-and-the-marches/review-160757.html |date=October 29, 2014 }}</ref> It is 93 meters long, 60 meters wide, and its campanile is 75.6 meters high.\n\nThe [[fa\u00e7ade]] of the church was erected under [[Pope Sixtus V|Sixtus&nbsp;V]], who in 1586 fortified Loreto and gave it the privileges of a town; his colossal statue stands on the [[parvis]], above the front steps, a third of the way to the left as one enters. Over the principal doorway there is a lifesize bronze statue of the Virgin and Child by [[Girolamo Lombardo]]; the three superb bronze doors executed at the latter end of the 16th century under the reign of [[Pope Paul V|Paul V]] (1605\u20131621) are also by Lombardo (1506-1590), his sons and his pupils, among them [[Tiburzio Vergelli]] (1551-1609), who also made the fine bronze [[baptismal font|font]] in the interior. The doors and hanging lamps are by the same artists.<ref name=fodors/>\n\nThe richly decorated [[campanile]] (1750 to 1754), by [[Luigi Vanvitelli]],<ref name=fodors/> is of great height; the principal bell, presented by [[Pope Leo X|Leo X]] in 1516, weighs 11 tons.\n\nThe interior of the church has [[mosaic]]s by [[Domenichino]] and [[Guido Reni]] and other works of art, including statues by [[Raffaello da Montelupo]]. In the [[Sacristy|sacristies]] on each side of the right [[transept]] are [[fresco]]es, on the right by [[Melozzo da Forl\u00ec]], on the left by [[Luca Signorelli]] and in both there are some fine [[intarsia]]s; the basilica as a whole is thus a collaborative work by generations of architects and artists.\n\n==The ''Santa Casa''==\n[[File:Santuario della Santa Casa in Loreto - Casa Santa.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Marble screen around the Holy House]]\n\nThe main attraction of Loreto is the Holy House itself (in [[Italian language|Italian]], the ''Santa Casa di Loreto''). It has been a [[Catholic]] pilgrimage destination since at least the 14th century and a popular tourist destination for non-Catholics as well.\n\n===Description===\n====The \"house\"====\nThe \"house\" itself is a plain stone building, 8.5&nbsp;m  by 3.8 m  and 4.1 m  high; it has a door on the north side and a window on the west. A niche contains a small [[black Madonna|black image of the Virgin and Child]], a statue in [[Lebanon cedar]], richly adorned with jewels (for more see [[Basilica della Santa Casa#Our Lady of Loreto|below]]).\n\n====The sculpted marble screen====\nAround the house is a tall marble screen designed by Bramante and executed under Popes Leo&nbsp;X, [[Pope Clement VII|Clement VII]] and [[Pope Paul III|Paul III]], by [[Andrea Sansovino]], Girolamo Lombardo, [[Bartolommeo Bandinelli|Bandinelli]], [[Guglielmo della Porta]] and others in the [[baroque]] style. The four sides represent the [[Annunciation]], the [[Nativity of Jesus in art|Nativity]], the Arrival of the Santa Casa at Loreto and the [[Nativity of the Blessed Virgin Mary|Nativity of the Virgin]], respectively.\n\n===The treasury===\nThe treasury contains a large variety of rich and curious votive offerings. The architectural design is finer than the details of the sculpture. The apse is decorated with 19th-century German frescoes.\n\n==Tradition==\n[[File:Loreto Fresko.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Fresco by [[Melozzo da Forl\u00ec]] in the sacristy of St Marc]]\n\nThe town has been a popular pilgrimage site{{for what|date=April 2020}} since the 13th century.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n===In Nazareth===\nLate medieval religious traditions developed suggesting that this was the house in which the [[Holy Family]] (Mary, Joseph and Jesus) had lived while in [[Judea (Roman province)|Judea]] at the start of the first century AD, and which was miraculously flown over to Europe by four angels just before the final expulsion of the Christian [[Crusaders]] from the [[Holy Land]], in order to protect it from [[Muslim]] soldiers. According to this narrative, the house at [[Nazareth]] in which [[Mary, the mother of Jesus|Mary]] had been born and brought up, potentially received the [[Annunciation]], and had lived during the childhood of Christ{{dubious|Is it really part of the legend? A married woman moved to her husband's house.|date=April 2020}} and after his [[Ascension of Jesus Christ|Ascension]], and was converted into a church by the [[Twelve Apostles]].{{dubious|Poor use of punctuation. Is it meant to say that she lived in the house after the Ascension, or that the Apostles made it into a church  after the Ascension? If the former, we do have different, strong post-Ascension traditions placing Mary in Jerusalem and Ephesus, NOT Nazareth.|date=April 2020}}{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn 336, [[Helena (Empress)|Empress Helena]] made a pilgrimage to Nazareth and allegedly directed that a basilica be erected over it, in which worship continued until the fall of the Crusader [[Kingdom of Jerusalem]]. However, there is no firm historical evidence that Helena did in fact make such a intervention.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n===To Dalmatia and Italy===\nThe tale further states that, threatened with destruction by Muslim soldiers, the house was miraculously carried by [[angel]]s through the air and initially deposited in 1291 on a hill at [[Tersatto]] (now Trsat, a suburb of [[Rijeka]], [[Croatia]]), where an appearance of the Virgin and numerous [[miracle|miraculous]] cures attested to its sanctity. The miraculous translation of the house is said to have been confirmed by investigations made at Nazareth by messengers from the governor of [[Dalmatia]]. In 1294, angels again carried it across the [[Adriatic Sea]] to the woods near [[Recanati]] (although the reasoning is not clear as to why this happened); from these woods (Latin ''lauretum'', Italian ''Colle dei Lauri'' or from the name of its proprietress Laureta) the chapel derived the name which it still retains (Lat. ''sacellum glorios\u00e6 Virginis in Laureto''). From this spot it was afterwards removed to the present hill in 1295, with a slight adjustment being required to fix it in its current site. It is this house that gave rise to the title ''Our Lady of Loreto'', sometimes applied to the Virgin; the miracle is occasionally represented in religious art wherein the house is borne by an angelic host.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Papal support===\n[[papal bull|Bulls]] in favour of the Shrine at Loreto were issued by [[Pope Sixtus IV|Pope Sixtus IV]] in 1491 (although, since Sixtus IV died in 1484, euther the date is erroneous, or else the pope should be Innocent VIII), and by [[Pope Julius II|Julius II]] in 1507, the last alluding to the translation of the house with some caution (''ut pie creditur et fama est''). While, like most miracles, the translation of the house is not a matter of faith for Catholics, nonetheless, in the late 17th century, [[Pope Innocent XII|Innocent XII]] appointed a ''missa cum officio proprio'' (a special [[mass]]) for the Feast of the Translation of the Holy House, which as late as the 20th century was enjoined in the [[Spanish Breviary]] as a [[Ranking of liturgical days in the Roman Rite#History|greater double]] on December 10. This mass was recently restored by Pope Francis in 2019.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nOn 4 October 2012, [[Benedict XVI]] visited the Shrine to mark the 50th anniversary of [[John XXIII]]'s visit. In his visit, Benedict formally entrusted the [[World Synod of Bishops]] and the Year of Faith to the Virgin of Loreto.<ref name=cns>{{cite news |title= Pope at Marian shrine entrusts Year of Faith, synod to Mary |url= http://www.catholicnews.com/data/stories/cns/1204169.htm |archive-url= http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20121205203916/http://www.catholicnews.com/data/stories/cns/1204169.htm |url-status= dead |archive-date=5 December 2012 |access-date=18 December 2012 |newspaper= Catholic News Service |date=4 October 2012 }}</ref><ref>[https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/benedict_xvi/homilies/2012/documents/hf_ben-xvi_hom_20121004_loreto_en.html Pastoral visit of Benedict XVI to Loreto] {{webarchive |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130102054537/https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/benedict_xvi/homilies/2012/documents/hf_ben-xvi_hom_20121004_loreto_en.html |date=2 January 2013 }}</ref><ref>[https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/benedict_xvi/prayers/documents/hf_ben-xvi_20070901_prayer-loreto_en.html Benedict XVI, Prayer to Our Lady of Loreto] {{webarchive |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130102120718/https://www.vatican.va/holy_father/benedict_xvi/prayers/documents/hf_ben-xvi_20070901_prayer-loreto_en.html |date= January 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Historicity==\nThe documented history of the house can only be traced as far back as the close of the [[Crusades]], around the 14th century. An early brief reference is made in the ''Italia Illustrata'' of [[Flavius Blondus]] (1392\u20131463), secretary to Popes [[Pope Eugene IV|Eugene&nbsp;IV]], [[Pope Nicholas V|Nicholas V]], [[Pope Calixtus III|Calixtus III]] and [[Pope Pius II|Pius II]]; it can be read in its entirety in the ''Redemptoris mundi Matris Ecclesi\u00e6 Lauretana historia'', by a certain Teremannus, contained in the ''Opera Omnia'' (1576) of [[Mantuanus|Baptista Mantuanus]].\n\n==History==\nAccording to [[Herbert Thurston]], in some respects the Lauretan tradition is \"beset with difficulties of the gravest kind\", which were noted in a 1906 work on the subject. There are documents which indicate that a church dedicated to the Blessed Virgin already existed at Loreto in the twelfth and thirteenth centuries, that is, 180 years before the time of the supposed translation; and there is no mention of the supposed miraculous translation of the Holy House in 1472. Thurston notes that papal confirmations of the Loreto tradition are relatively late (the first Bull mentioning the translation is that of Julius II in 1507), but that they are at first very guarded in expression, for Julius introduces the clause \"''ut pie creditur et fama est''\", \"as is piously believed and reported to be\".<ref name=Thurston>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/13454b.htm Thurston, Herbert. \"Santa Casa di Loreto.\" The Catholic Encyclopedia] Vol. 13. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1912. 10 December 2017</ref> Thurston suggests that a miracle-working statue or picture of the Madonna was brought from Tersato in [[Illyria]] to Loreto by some pious Christians and was then confounded with the ancient rustic chapel in which it was harboured, the veneration formerly given to the statue afterwards passing to the building.<ref name=Thurston/>\n\nFinally, he draws comparisons to the shrine at [[Our Lady of Walsingham|Walsingham]], the principal English shrine of the Blessed Virgin, the legend of \"Our Lady's house\" (written down about 1465, and consequently earlier than the Loreto translation tradition) supposes that in the time of St. Edward the Confessor a chapel was built at Walsingham, which exactly reproduced the dimensions of the Holy House of Nazareth. When the carpenters could not complete it upon the site that had been chosen, it was transferred and erected by angels' hands at a spot two hundred feet away.<ref>\"The Month\", September 1901</ref>\n\nIn modern times, the Church traced the linguistic origins of the story to a local aristocratic family called \"Angelos\", which were responsible for the transfer.<ref name=kerr>{{cite news|last=Kerr|first=David|title=Pope entrusts Year of Faith, evangelization synod to Mary|url=http://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/pope-entrusts-year-of-faith-evangelization-synod-to-mary/|accessdate=18 December 2012|newspaper=Catholic News Agency|date=4 October 2012}}</ref> According to Papal archivist Giuseppe Lapponi, it seems that a family by the name of Angeli saved the bricks of the Holy House from the Muslim invasion. Excavations beneath the House of Loreto found coins, two of which are connected to the Angeli family.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://udayton.edu/imri/mary/o/our-lady-of-loreto-and-aviation.php |title=Roten SM, Johann. \"Our Lady of Loreto and Aviation\", International Marian Research Institute, University of Dayton |publisher=Udayton.edu |date=1920-03-24 |accessdate=2020-01-19}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Our Lady of Loreto.jpg|thumb|The venerated Marian image of ''Our Lady of Loreto''. The cedar wood was timbered from the [[Vatican Gardens]].]]\n\n==Our Lady of Loreto==\n'''Our Lady of Loreto''' is the title of the Virgin Mary with respect to the Holy House of Loreto. Her statue, carved from Cedar of Lebanon, is a \"[[Black Madonna]],\" owing to centuries of lamp smoke.{{dubious|Maybe the original one, but this one's from 1922. Chaos!|date=March 2020}} It, like the Holy House, is associated with miracles. In the 1600s a Mass and a Marian litany was approved. This \"Litany of Loreto\" is the [[Litany of the Blessed Virgin Mary]], one of the five litanies approved for public recitation by the Church. In 1920 [[Pope Benedict XV]] declared the Madonna of Loreto [[patron saint]] of air travellers and pilots.<ref>[http://www.ewtn.com/v/experts/showmessage.asp?number=444755 Donovan, Colin B., \"Our Lady of Loreto\", EWTN, August 2, 2005]{{dead link|date=January 2020}}</ref> The statue was commissioned after a fire in the Santa Casa in 1921 destroyed the original madonna, and it was granted a [[Canonical Coronation]] in 1922 by [[Pope Pius XI]]. In October 2019 [[Pope Francis]] restored the feast of Our Lady of Loreto, commemorated on December 10, to the universal Roman calendar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://catholicnewsherald.com/news/world/93-news/vatican/5082-pope-adds-feast-of-our-lady-of-loreto-to-universal-calendar |title=Pope adds feast of Our Lady of Loreto to universal calendar |publisher=Catholicnewsherald.com |date=2019-10-31 |accessdate=2020-01-19}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|Santuario della Santa Casa (Loreto)}}\n\n* [[Basilica of the Annunciation]] in Nazareth\n* [[House of the Virgin Mary]]\n* [[Giovanni Tonucci]]\n* [[Territorial prelature of Loreto]]\n* [[Church of Our Lady of Loreto|Loreto Church]] in [[Warsaw]]\n* [[Loreta]] in [[Prague]]\n* [[Our Lady of Loreto and St Winefride's, Kew]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last=Grimaldi|first=Floriano |title=La Chiesa di Santa Maria di Loreto nei documenti dei secoli XII - XV|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cg6lugEACAAJ|year=1984|publisher=Stabilimento Tipografico Mierma|location=Ancona|language=Italian, Latin}}\n*{{cite book|last=Grimaldi|first=Floriano |title=La historia della Chiesa di Santa Maria de Loreto|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a92KEzlvzdIC|year=1993|publisher=Carilo|location=Loreto|language=Italian}}\n*{{cite book|last=Hutchison|first=William Antony|title=Loreto and Nazareth: Two Lectures, Containing the Results of Personal Investigation of the Two Sanctuaries|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4yBDgxav7dYC&pg=PP13|year=1863|publisher=E. Dillon|location=London}}\n*{{cite book|last=Leopardi|first=Monaldo|title=La Santa Casa di Loreto: discussioni istoriche e critiche|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dvsdUdTijGoC&pg=PA1|year=1841|publisher=presso Francesco Veladini e C.|location=Lugano|language=Italian}}\n*{{cite book|first=Karin|last=V\u00e9lez|title=The Miraculous Flying House of Loreto: Spreading Catholicism in the Early Modern World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VT5hDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA127|year=2018|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-0-691-18449-4}}\n\n::{{catholic|title=Santa Casa di Loreto}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.santuarioloreto.it/default_eng.htm Sanctuary of Loreto] - Official site\n{{portal bar|Architecture|Catholicism|Italy}}\n{{coord|43.44095|N|13.610578|E|source:itwiki_region:IT|format=dms|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Holy See}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Basilica Della Santa Casa}}\n[[Category:Basilica churches in the Marche|Casa Santa]]\n[[Category:Catholic pilgrimage sites]]\n[[Category:Marian shrines]]\n[[Category:Properties of the Holy See]]\n[[Category:Loreto, Marche]]\n", "name_user": "Arminden", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePapal support", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basilica_della_Santa_Casa"}
{"title_page": "Liga Okr\u0119gowa", "text_new": "{{short description|League in sixth level of Polish football}}\n{{unreferenced|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{ infobox football league\n| name                 = Liga Okr\u0119gowa\n| image                = \n| pixels               = \n| country              = [[Poland]]\n| confed               = \n| founded              = \n| teams                = 1000+ (in 2019/20)\n| promotion            = [[IV liga]]\n| relegation           = [[Klasa A]]\n| levels               = [[Polish football league system|6]]\n| domest_cup           = [[Polish Cup]]\n| champions            = \n| season               = \n| most successful club = \n| website              = \n| current              = \n}}\n'''Liga Okr\u0119gowa''' or '''Klasa Okr\u0119gowa''' is a regional league divided into 58 groups and represents the sixth level of the [[Polish football league system|Polish football hierarchy]]. These groups represent all the voivodeships (provinces) of Poland.\n\nGenerally, teams promoted from Liga Okr\u0119gowa move up to the [[IV liga|IV Liga]], whilst relegated teams descend to the {{ill|Klasa A|lt=Klasa A|pl|Klasa A}} leagues.\n\nThis is not currently true for the voivodeship of [[Greater Poland Voivodeship|Greater Poland]](wojew\u00f3dztwo wielkopolskie) where a V Liga exists, here the Liga Okr\u0119gowa corresponds to the seventh level of the hierarchy, the sixth being the V Liga, teams promoted from Liga Okr\u0119gowa move up to the V Liga, whilst relegated teams descend to the Klasa A leagues.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.90minut.pl/ligireg.php?id_sezon=95 Ligi regionalne 2019/20] {{in lang|pl}}\n\n{{Football in Poland}}\n{{UEFA sixth level leagues}}\n\n[[Category:Football leagues in Poland|6]]\n[[Category:Sixth level football leagues in Europe|Poland]]\n\n{{Poland-footy-competition-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|League in sixth level of Polish football}}\n{{unreferenced|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{ infobox football league\n| name                 = Liga Okr\u0119gowa\n| image                = \n| pixels               = \n| country              = [[Poland]]\n| confed               = \n| founded              = \n| teams                = 1000+ (in 2019/20)\n| promotion            = [[IV liga]]\n| relegation           = [[Klasa A]]\n| levels               = [[Polish football league system|6]]\n| domest_cup           = [[Polish Cup]]\n| champions            = \n| season               = \n| most successful club = \n| website              = \n| current              = \n}}\n'''Liga Okr\u0119gowa''' or '''Klasa Okr\u0119gowa''' is a regional league divided into 58 groups and represents the sixth level of the [[Polish football league system|Polish football hierarchy]]. These groups represent all the voivodeships (provinces) of Poland.\n\nGenerally, teams promoted from Liga Okr\u0119gowa move up to the [[IV liga|IV Liga]], whilst relegated teams descend to the {{ill|Klasa A|lt=Klasa A|pl|Klasa A}} leagues.\n\nThis is not currently true for the voivodeship of Greater Poland (wojew\u00f3dztwo wielkopolskie) where a V Liga exists, here the Liga Okr\u0119gowa corresponds to the seventh level of the hierarchy, the sixth being the V Liga, teams promoted from Liga Okr\u0119gowa move up to the V Liga, whilst relegated teams descend to the Klasa A leagues.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.90minut.pl/ligireg.php?id_sezon=95 Ligi regionalne 2019/20] {{in lang|pl}}\n\n{{Football in Poland}}\n{{UEFA sixth level leagues}}\n\n[[Category:Football leagues in Poland|6]]\n[[Category:Sixth level football leagues in Europe|Poland]]\n\n{{Poland-footy-competition-stub}}\n", "name_user": "JohnAKaye", "label": "safe", "comment": "added wielkopolski link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liga_Okr%C4%99gowa"}
{"title_page": "Ronaldo Senfft", "text_new": "{{short description|Brazilian sailor}}\n{{MedalTableTop | medals = \n{{MedalSport | [[Sailing (sport)|Sailing]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{BRA}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Sailing at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]] }}\n{{MedalSilver | [[1984 Summer Olympics|1984 Los Angeles]] | [[Sailing at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Soling|Soling class]] }}\n}}\n'''Ronaldo Camargo Ribeiro Senfft''' (born July 12, 1954) is a [[Brazil]]ian [[sailor]]. He won the Silver medal in the [[Sailing at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Soling|Soling class]] at the [[1984 Summer Olympics]] in [[Los Angeles]] along with [[Daniel Adler (sailor)|Daniel Adler]] and [[Torben Grael]].<ref>{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/se/ronaldo-senfft-1.html |title=Ronaldo Senfft |accessdate=2013-06-18}}</ref><ref name=\"Nauright2012\">{{cite book |author=John Nauright |title=Sports around the World |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mYBtMajLAaAC&pg=RA3-PA153 |accessdate=19 June 2013 |date=6 April 2012 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |isbn=978-1-59884-301-9 |page=153}}</ref><ref name=\"Rubio2006\">{{cite book |author=Katia Rubio |title=Medalhistas Olimpicos Brasileiros Memorias, |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l7DJG-ZezEAC&pg=PA213 |accessdate=19 June 2013 |year=2006 |publisher=Casa do Psic\u00f3logo |language=Portuguese |isbn=978-85-7396-439-4 |pages=213\u2013}}</ref>\n{{Footer North American Champions Soling}}\n{{Footer Brazilian Championship Winners in Soling}}\n{{Footer Canadian Championship Winners in Soling}}\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n[[Category:North American Champion Soling]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Senfft, Ronaldo}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Brazilian male sailors (sport)]]\n[[Category:Olympic sailors of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in sailing]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Soling]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1984 Summer Olympics]]\n\n\n{{Brazil-yachtracing-bio-stub}}\n{{Brazil-Olympic-medalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Brazilian sailor}}\n{{MedalTableTop | medals = \n{{MedalSport | [[Sailing (sport)|Sailing]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{BRA}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Sailing at the Summer Olympics|Olympic Games]] }}\n{{MedalSilver | [[1984 Summer Olympics|1984 Los Angeles]] | [[Sailing at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Soling|Soling class]] }}\n}}\n'''Ronaldo Camargo Ribeiro Senfft''' (born July 12, 1954) is a [[Brazil]]ian [[sailor]]. He won the Silver medal in the [[Sailing at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Soling|Soling class]] at the [[1984 Summer Olympics]] in [[Los Angeles]] along with [[Daniel Adler (sailor)|Daniel Adler]] and [[Torben Grael]].<ref>{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/se/ronaldo-senfft-1.html |title=Ronaldo Senfft |accessdate=2013-06-18}}</ref><ref name=\"Nauright2012\">{{cite book |author=John Nauright |title=Sports around the World |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mYBtMajLAaAC&pg=RA3-PA153 |accessdate=19 June 2013 |date=6 April 2012 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |isbn=978-1-59884-301-9 |page=153}}</ref><ref name=\"Rubio2006\">{{cite book |author=Katia Rubio |title=Medalhistas Olimpicos Brasileiros Memorias, |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l7DJG-ZezEAC&pg=PA213 |accessdate=19 June 2013 |year=2006 |publisher=Casa do Psic\u00f3logo |language=Portuguese |isbn=978-85-7396-439-4 |pages=213\u2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n[[Category:North American Champion Soling]]\n{{Footer North American Champions Soling}}\n{{Footer Brazilian Championship Winners in Soling}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Senfft, Ronaldo}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Brazilian male sailors (sport)]]\n[[Category:Olympic sailors of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medalists for Brazil]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in sailing]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sailors at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Soling]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1984 Summer Olympics]]\n\n\n{{Brazil-yachtracing-bio-stub}}\n{{Brazil-Olympic-medalist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Dragon Genoa", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ronaldo_Senfft"}
{"title_page": "Gears Tactics", "text_new": "{{Infobox video game\n| title = Gears Tactics\n| image = File:Gears Tactics Steam promotional artwork.jpg\n| developer = [[Splash Damage]]<br/>[[The Coalition (company)|The Coalition]]\n| publisher = [[Xbox Game Studios]]\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]]<br/>[[Xbox One]]\n| designer = Tyler Bielman\n| series = ''[[Gears of War]]''\n| genre = [[Turn-based tactics]]\n| released = April 28, 2020\n| modes = [[Single-player]]\n}}\n\n'''''Gears Tactics''''' is an upcoming [[turn-based tactics]] video game developed by [[Splash Damage]] in conjunction with [[The Coalition (company)|The Coalition]] and published by [[Xbox Game Studios]]. As a [[spin-off]] of the ''[[Gears of War]]'' franchise and a prequel to the [[Gears of War (video game)|first game]], ''Tactics'' is set to be released for [[Microsoft Windows]] on April 28, 2020. A [[Xbox One]] version is also currently in development.\n\n==Gameplay==\nThe game is played from a [[top-down perspective]] and is a [[turn-based tactics]] title in which players issue commands to a squad of human soldiers to eliminate the hostiles in a map and dependent on missions, complete secondary objectives. Unlike ''[[XCOM: Enemy Unknown]]'', players can freely explore the map without being confined to a [[grid]]. Each character can perform three actions, such as taking cover, shooting enmies, or remain in [[overwatch]] to shoot any moving enemy in their [[line of sight]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kotaku.com.au/2020/03/gears-tactics-preview/|title=Gears Tactics Is An Authentic, Hybrid Strategy Game|first=Leah|last=Williams|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=March 28, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> When an enemy unit loses most of its [[health (gaming)|health]], a friendly unit can move in and [[execute]] the downed enemy, which gives all units an additional action point. Players also need to throw [[grenade]]s into destroy erupting Emergence Holes which would spawn more Locust enemies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2020-03-27-gears-tactics-is-more-gears-of-war-than-you-think|title=Gears Tactics is more Gears of War than you think|first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> If a friendly unit sustains too much damage, players may need to revive them, though they will still lose a significant portion of their health. The game has five distinct [[character classes]], with each having its own unique abilities. The characters can be extensively customized with mods, armours, and they can acquire new skills after they [[level up]]. A  [[permadeath]] system was featured in the game. Other than the two central characters, other friendly units are [[procedurally generated]] and should they are killed in combat, their deaths are permanent.<ref name=\"IGNPre\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/gears-tactics-preview-gears-of-war-meets-xcom-and-were-here-for-it|title=Gears Tactics Preview: Gears of War Meets XCOM and We're Here for It|first=Miranda|last=Sanchez|work=[[IGN]]|date=March 28, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>  \n\nIn addition to the main campaign, players can also complete different side-missions. After the player finishes the campaign, Veteran Mode will be unlocked. It allows players to remix the campaign missions with different modifiers such as bonus damages and accuracy penalty.<ref name=\"IGNPre\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/gears-tactics-is-a-shockingly-good-strategy-game/|title=Gears Tactics is a shockingly good strategy game|first=Wes|last=Fenlon|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=March 28, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> The game, however, does not have a [[multiplayer]] mode.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/gears-tactics-gets-new-trailer-and-april-release-date-wont-have-multiplayer-or-microtransactions/|title=Gears Tactics gets new trailer and April release date, won't have multiplayer or microtransactions|first=Jordan|last=Gerbick|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=December 13, 2019|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Story==\nThe game is a prequel to the first ''[[Gears of War]]''. The story follows Gabe Diaz, the father of Kait Diaz (the protagonist of ''[[Gears 5]]''), who embarcks on a secret mission with fellow [[Coalition of Ordered Governments]] soldier Sid Redburn to assassinate Ukkon, a locust scientists who is involved in breeding dangerous monsters for the locust horde.<ref name=\"GIPre\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/preview/2020/03/27/gears-tactics-might-have-what-it-takes-to-compete-with-xcom|title=Gears Tactics Might Have What It Takes To Compete With XCOM|first=Ben|last=Reeves|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\nThe game's development was handled by [[Splash Damage]] with [[The Coalition (company)|The Coalition]] providing assistance. The Coalition wanted to introduce the franchise to a wider audience and the development team identified that there were a lot of similarities between the franchise, which was a series of squad-based [[third-person shooter]]s with cover-based combat, and [[turn-based strategy]] games.<ref name=\"GIPre\"/> According to Alex Grimbley, the game's executive producer, \"[the team] actually just took existing Gears and just moved the camera up\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/gears-tactics/developer-interview|title=\u201cWe just moved the camera up\u201d \u2013 why Gears Tactics makes so much sense|first=Richard|last=Scott=Jones|work=[[PCGamesN]]|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> The team took four and a half year to develop the game.<ref name=\"Cole\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/what-you-need-to-know-about-gears-tactics-the-new-/1100-6475295/|title=What You Need To Know About Gears Tactics, The New PC Strategy Game|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe team wanted the game to have faster pace when compared with its competitors. Thus the team decides to give each unit's three action points instead of two to ensure that players can get to perform various actions within one turn.<ref name=\"IGNPre\"/> The team also put a large emphasis on the game's narrative, and the team aimed to tell a \"personal and emotional story\" and invested a lot of resources into creating the game's [[cutscene]]s and employing the voice actors. The team also consulted [[343 Industries]], which worked on ''[[Halo Wars]]'', a strategy spin-off of the ''[[Halo]]'' franchise. However, unlike ''Halo Wars'', the game was consdiered to be a PC premium title instead of a strategy game designed for console owners.<ref name=\"IGNPre\"/> \n\nPublisher [[Xbox Game Studios]] announced the game at [[E3 2017]], alongside ''[[Gears 5]]'' and ''[[Gears Pop!]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/06/10/microsoft-unveils-gears-of-war-5-gears-pop-and-gears-tactics/|title=Microsoft unveils Gears of War 5, Gears Pop, and Gears Tactics|first=Dean|last=Takahashi|work=[[VentureBeat]]|date=June 10, 2018|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> At [[The Game Awards 2019]], Microsoft announced that the game would be released for Windows on April 28, 2020, while [[Rod Fergusson]], the founder of the Coalition, later confirmed that a Xbox One version is being developed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/12/13/gears-tactics-release-date-revealed|title=Gears Tactics Release Date Revealed|first=Miranda|last=Sanchez|work=[[IGN]]|date=December 13, 2019|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Players who pre-ordered the game would gain access to the \"Thrashball Cole\" pack, which allows the player to play as [[Augustus Cole]].<ref name=\"Cole\"/> The game was also released for [[Xbox Game Pass]] subscribers at launch.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/gears-tactics-has-gone-gold-on-pc-will-be-bundled-/1100-6475767/|title=Gears Tactics Has Gone Gold On PC, Will Be Bundled Free With Intel Processors|first=James|last=O'Connor|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=April 7, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.gearstactics.com/}}\n{{Gears of War series}}\n\n[[Category:Upcoming video games scheduled for 2020]]\n[[Category:Gears of War]]\n[[Category:Splash Damage games]]\n[[Category:Tactical role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Dystopian video games]]\n[[Category:Turn-based tactics video games]]\n[[Category:Unreal Engine games]]\n[[Category:Video game prequels]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Canada]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox video game\n| title = Gears Tactics\n| image = File:Gears Tactics Steam promotional artwork.jpg\n| developer = [[Splash Damage]]<br/>[[The Coalition (company)|The Coalition]]\n| publisher = [[Xbox Game Studios]]\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]]<br/>[[Xbox One]]\n| designer = Tyler Bielman\n| series = ''[[Gears of War]]''\n| genre = [[Turn-based tactics]]\n| released = April 28, 2020\n| modes = [[Single-player]]\n}}\n\n'''''Gears Tactics''''' is an upcoming [[turn-based tactics]] video game developed by [[Splash Damage]] in conjunction with [[The Coalition (company)|The Coalition]] and published by [[Xbox Game Studios]]. As a [[spin-off]] of the ''[[Gears of War]]'' franchise and a prequel to the [[Gears of War (video game)|first game]], ''Tactics'' is set to be released for [[Microsoft Windows]] on April 28, 2020. A [[Xbox One]] version is also currently in development.\n\n==Gameplay==\nThe game is played from a [[top-down perspective]] and is a [[turn-based tactics]] title in which players issue commands to a squad of human soldiers to eliminate the hostiles in a map and dependent on missions, complete secondary objectives. Unlike ''[[XCOM: Enemy Unknown]]'', players can freely explore the map without being confined to a [[grid]]. Each character can perform three actions, such as taking cover, shooting enmies, or remain in [[overwatch]] to shoot any moving enemy in their [[line of sight]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kotaku.com.au/2020/03/gears-tactics-preview/|title=Gears Tactics Is An Authentic, Hybrid Strategy Game|first=Leah|last=Williams|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=March 28, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> When an enemy unit loses most of its [[health (gaming)|health]], a friendly unit can move in and [[execute]] the downed enemy, which gives all units an additional action point. Players also need to throw [[grenade]]s into destroy erupting Emergence Holes which would spawn more Locust enemies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2020-03-27-gears-tactics-is-more-gears-of-war-than-you-think|title=Gears Tactics is more Gears of War than you think|first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> If a friendly unit sustains too much damage, players may need to revive them, though they will still lose a significant portion of their health. The game has five distinct [[character classes]], with each having its own unique abilities. The characters can be extensively customized with mods, armours, and they can acquire new skills after they [[level up]]. A  [[permadeath]] system was featured in the game. Other than the two central characters, other friendly units are [[procedurally generated]] and should they are killed in combat, their deaths are permanent.<ref name=\"IGNPre\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/gears-tactics-preview-gears-of-war-meets-xcom-and-were-here-for-it|title=Gears Tactics Preview: Gears of War Meets XCOM and We're Here for It|first=Miranda|last=Sanchez|work=[[IGN]]|date=March 28, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>  \n\nIn addition to the main campaign, players can also complete different side-missions. After the player finishes the campaign, Veteran Mode will be unlocked. It allows players to remix the campaign missions with different modifiers such as bonus damages and accuracy penalty.<ref name=\"IGNPre\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/gears-tactics-is-a-shockingly-good-strategy-game/|title=Gears Tactics is a shockingly good strategy game|first=Wes|last=Fenlon|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=March 28, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> The game, however, does not have a [[multiplayer]] mode.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/gears-tactics-gets-new-trailer-and-april-release-date-wont-have-multiplayer-or-microtransactions/|title=Gears Tactics gets new trailer and April release date, won't have multiplayer or microtransactions|first=Jordan|last=Gerbick|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=December 13, 2019|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Story==\nThe game is a prequel to the first ''[[Gears of War]]''. The story follows Gabe Diaz, the father of Kait Diaz (the protagonist of ''[[Gears 5]]''), who embarcks on a secret mission with fellow [[Coalition of Ordered Governments]] soldier Sid Redburn to assassinate Ukkon, a locust scientists who is involved in breeding dangerous monsters for the locust horde.<ref name=\"GIPre\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gameinformer.com/preview/2020/03/27/gears-tactics-might-have-what-it-takes-to-compete-with-xcom|title=Gears Tactics Might Have What It Takes To Compete With XCOM|first=Ben|last=Reeves|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\nThe game's development was handled by [[Splash Damage]] with [[The Coalition (company)|The Coalition]] providing assistance. The Coalition wanted to introduce the franchise to a wider audience and the development team identified that there were a lot of similarities between the franchise, which was a series of squad-based [[third-person shooter]]s with cover-based combat, and [[turn-based strategy]] games.<ref name=\"GIPre\"/> According to Alex Grimbley, the game's executive producer, \"[the team] actually just took existing Gears and just moved the camera up\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/gears-tactics/developer-interview|title=\u201cWe just moved the camera up\u201d \u2013 why Gears Tactics makes so much sense|first=Richard|last=Scott=Jones|work=[[PCGamesN]]|date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> The team took four and a half year to develop the game.<ref name=\"Cole\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/what-you-need-to-know-about-gears-tactics-the-new-/1100-6475295/|title=What You Need To Know About Gears Tactics, The New PC Strategy Game|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe team wanted the game to have faster pace when compared with its competitors. Thus the team decides to give each unit's three action points instead of two to ensure that players can get to perform various actions within one turn.<ref name=\"IGNPre\"/> The team also put a large emphasis on the game's narrative, and the team aimed to tell a \"personal and emotional story\" and invested a lot of resources into creating the game's [[cutscene]]s and employing the voice actors. The team also consulted [[343 Industries]], which worked on ''[[Halo Wars]]'', a strategy spin-off of the ''[[Halo]]'' franchise. However, unlike ''Halo Wars'', the game was consdiered to be a PC premium title instead of a strategy game designed for console owners.<ref name=\"IGNPre\"/> \n\nPublisher [[Xbox Game Studios]] announced the game at [[E3 2017]], alongside ''[[Gears 5]]'' and ''[[Gears Pop!]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/06/10/microsoft-unveils-gears-of-war-5-gears-pop-and-gears-tactics/|title=Microsoft unveils Gears of War 5, Gears Pop, and Gears Tactics|first=Dean|last=Takahashi|work=[[VentureBeat]]|date=June 10, 2018|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> At [[The Game Awards 2019]], Microsoft announced that the game would be released for Windows on April 28, 2020, while [[Rod Fergusson]], the founder of the Coalition, later confirmed that a Xbox One version is being developed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/12/13/gears-tactics-release-date-revealed|title=Gears Tactics Release Date Revealed|first=Miranda|last=Sanchez|work=[[IGN]]|date=December 13, 2019|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Players who pre-ordered the game would gain access to the \"Thrashball Cole\" pack, which allows the player to play as [[Augustus Cole]].<ref name=\"Cole\"/> The game was also released for [[Xbox Game Pass]] subscribers at launch.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/gears-tactics-has-gone-gold-on-pc-will-be-bundled-/1100-6475767/|title=Gears Tactics Has Gone Gold On PC, Will Be Bundled Free With Intel Processors|first=James|last=O'Connor|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=April 7, 2020|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.gearstactics.com/}}\n{{Gears of War series}}\n\n[[Category:Upcoming video games scheduled for 2020]]\n[[Category:Gears of War]]\n[[Category:Splash Damage games]]\n[[Category:Tactical role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Dystopian video games]]\n[[Category:Turn-based tactics video games]]\n[[Category:Unreal Engine games]]\n[[Category:Video game prequels]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Canada]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United Kingdoms]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n", "name_user": "OceanHok", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gears_Tactics"}
{"title_page": "Simon Schama", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name        = Sir Simon Schama\n| honorific_suffix = [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]], [[Fellow of the British Academy|FBA]], [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Literature|FRSL]]\n| image       = Simon Schama FT.jpg\n| image_size  = 200px\n| caption     = Schama in 2013\n| birth_name  = Simon Michael Schama\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1945|02|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Marylebone, London]], England\n| residence   = [[Briarcliff Manor, New York]], U.S.\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| occupation  = Academic, [[art history|art historian]]\n| education   = [[Haberdashers' Aske's Boys' School]]\n| alma_mater  = [[Christ's College, Cambridge]]\n| spouse      = Virginia Papaioannou\n| children    = 2\n| awards      = [[Wolfson History Prize]]<br />[[Leo Gershoy Award]]<br />[[Fellow of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n| module      = <center>{{Listen|embed=yes|filename=Simon Schama BBC Radio4 Start the Week 30 December 2013 b03mcmwx.flac|title=<center>Simon Schama's voice</center>|type=speech|description=<center>[[:File:Simon Schama BBC Radio4 Start the Week 30 December 2013 b03mcmwx.flac|Recorded December 2013]] from the BBC Radio 4 programme ''[[Start the Week]]''</center>}}</center>\n}}\n\n'''Sir Simon Michael Schama''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CBE|FBA|FRSL}} ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0283|\u00e6|m|\u0259}}; born 13 February 1945) is an English historian specialising in [[art history]], [[Dutch history]], Jewish history and [[French history]].<ref name=\"snowman\"/> He is a University Professor of History and Art History at [[Columbia University]], New York.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.culpa.info/professors/568|title=Columbia student reviews of Schama's teaching|date=2005|website=CULPA}}</ref>\n\nHe first came to public attention with his history of the [[French Revolution]] titled ''[[Citizens: A Chronicle of the French Revolution|Citizens]]'', published in 1989.<ref name=\"snowman\"/> In the United Kingdom, he is perhaps best known for writing and hosting the 15-part BBC television documentary series ''[[Simon Schama's A History of Britain|A History of Britain]]'' broadcast between 2000 and 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b008qpzn/episodes/guide|title=BBC Two - A History of Britain by Simon Schama - Episode guide|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2000/oct/01/historybooks.robertmccrum|title=Observer review: A History of Britain by Simon Schama|last=McCrum|first=Robert|date=2000-09-30|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref> Schama was [[knighted]] in the [[2018 Queen's Birthday Honours]] List.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/62310/supplement/B1 |title=Honours list|date=2018 |website= www.thegazette.co.uk|publisher=|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nSchama was born in [[Marylebone]], London.<ref name=\"snowman\">{{cite journal | last1 = Snowman | first1 = Daniel | author1-link = Daniel Snowman | year = 2004 | title = Simon Schama | journal = History Today | volume = 54 | issue = 7| pages = 34\u201336 | url = https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-0-230-59997-0_24 }}</ref><ref name=\"JC background 1\">{{cite news|url=http://website.thejc.com/home.aspx?AId=46437&ATypeId=1&search=true2&srchtxt=1&srchhead=1&srchauthor=1&srchsandp=1&scsrch=0|author= Silverstone, Ben|title=Schama's art of making history|work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]|accessdate=23 July 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005064559/http://website.thejc.com/home.aspx?AId=46437&ATypeId=1&search=true2&srchtxt=1&srchhead=1&srchauthor=1&srchsandp=1&scsrch=0|archivedate=5 October 2011}}</ref> His mother, Gertie (n\u00e9e Steinberg), was from an [[Ashkenazi]] Jewish family (from [[Kaunas]], present-day [[Lithuania]]), and his father, Arthur Schama, was of [[Sephardi]] Jewish background (from Smyrna, present-day [[\u0130zmir]] in Turkey), later moving through Moldova and Romania.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishtelegraph.com/prof_217.html|last=Wachmann |first=Doreen |title=Profile: Biblical Tales Gave Schama his First Taste for History |date=2013 |work=[[Jewish Telegraph]]|publisher=Jewishtelegraph.com|accessdate=26 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejc.com/112351/simon-schama-interview|title=Simon Schama Interview &#124; The Jewish Chronicle|publisher=Thejc.com|date=12 October 2013|accessdate=26 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the mid-1940s, the family moved to [[Southend-on-Sea]] in Essex before moving back to London. In 1956, Schama won a scholarship to the private [[Haberdashers' Aske's Boys' School]] in [[Cricklewood]], (from 1961 [[Elstree]], Hertfordshire). He then studied history at [[Christ's College, Cambridge]], where he was taught by [[John H. Plumb]]. He graduated from the [[University of Cambridge]] with a [[British undergraduate degree classification#Variations of first-class honours|Starred First]] in 1966.<ref name=\"snowman\"/>\n\n==Career==\nSchama worked for short periods as a lecturer in history at Cambridge, where he was a Fellow and Director of Studies in History at [[Christ's College, Cambridge |Christ's College]]. He then taught for some time at [[Oxford University|Oxford]], where he was made a Fellow of [[Brasenose College]] in 1976, specialising in the [[French Revolution]].<ref name=\"snowman\"/>\n\nAt this time, Schama wrote his first book, ''Patriots and Liberators'', which won the [[Wolfson History Prize]]. The book was originally intended as a study of the French Revolution, but as published in 1977, it focused on the effect of the ''[[Patriottentijd]]'' revolution of the 1780s in the Netherlands, and its [[Batavian Republic|aftermath]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.harpercollins.co.uk/9780006861560/patriots-and-liberators/|title=Patriots and Liberators by Simon Schama - Paperback {{!}} HarperCollins|work=HarperCollins UK|access-date=2018-09-16|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/1999/oct/16/books.guardianreview10|title=History, his way|date=1999-10-16|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref>\n\nHis second book, ''Two Rothschilds and the Land of Israel'' (1978), is a study of the [[Zionism|Zionist]] aims of [[Edmond James de Rothschild|Edmond]] and [[James Armand de Rothschild|James Rothschild]].\n\n===In the United States===\n[[File:Simon Schama at The Strand by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|Schama at New York City's [[Strand Bookstore]] in 2006.]]\nIn 1980, Schama took up a chair at [[Harvard University]]. His next book, ''The Embarrassment of Riches'' (1987), again focused on Dutch history.<ref name=\"TEOR publication 1\">Daniel, M., and S. Steinberg. \"Simon Schama.\" Publishers Weekly 238, No. 22 (17 May 1991): 46. Academic Search Premier, EBSCOhost (accessed 30 April 2009).</ref> Schama interpreted the ambivalences that informed the [[Dutch Golden Age]] of the 17th century, held in balance between the conflicting imperatives, to live richly and with power, or to live a godly life. The iconographic evidence that Schama draws upon, in 317 illustrations, of emblems and propaganda that defined Dutch character, prefigured his expansion in the 1990s as a commentator on art and visual culture.<ref name=\"TEOR commentator 1\">Adams, Julia; Stoler, Ann (November 1988). \"The Embarrassment of Riches: An Interpretation of Dutch Culture in the Golden Age, by Simon Schama\" (review). ''[[Contemporary Sociology]]''. '''17'''.6: 760\u201362. \"He provides a reading of cultural tints and social textures at a level of visual detail that is usually reserved for art history.\" {{doi|10.2307/2073570}}</ref>\n\n''Citizens'' (1989), written at speed to a publisher's commission, saw the publication of his long-awaited study of the [[French Revolution]], and won the 1990 [[NCR Book Award]]. Its view that the violence of the Terror was inherent from the start of the Revolution, however, has received serious negative criticism.<ref name=\"snowman\"/><ref name=\"Citizens 1989 1\">Notably in Timothy Tackett, \"Interpreting the Terror\" ''French Historical Studies'' '''24'''.4 (Autumn 2001:569\u2013578); Tackett's view of swiftly evolving revolution in his [[prosopography]] of the deputies, ''Becoming a Revolutionary: The Deputies of the French National Assembly and the Emergence of a Revolutionary Culture, 1789\u20131790'' (Princeton University Press) 1996, was not fundamentally at variance with Schama.</ref>\n\nSchama appeared as an on-screen expert in [[Michael Wood (historian)|Michael Wood]]'s 1989 PBS series, ''Art of the Western World'' as a presenting art historian, commenting on paintings by [[Diego Vel\u00e1zquez]], [[Rembrandt]], and [[Johannes Vermeer]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Art of the Western World (TV Series 1989\u2013 )|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0363314/fullcredits|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, he published ''Dead Certainties (Unwarranted Speculations)'',<ref name=\"Halttunen DC published 1\">{{Cite journal|jstor=2080071|last=Halttunen|first=Karen|title=Review of \"Dead Certainties (Unwarranted Speculations) by Simon Schama|work=The Journal of American History|volume=79| issue =  2 |date=September 1992|page=631}}</ref> a relatively slender work of unusual structure and point-of-view in that it looked at two widely reported deaths a hundred years apart, that of British Army General [[James Wolfe]] in 1759 \u2013 and the famous 1770 [[The Death of General Wolfe|painting depicting the event]] by [[Benjamin West]] \u2013 and that of [[George Parkman]], murdered uncle of the better known 19th-century American historian [[Francis Parkman]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/simon-schama-on-dead-certainties-historians-shouldnt-make-it-up-but-i-did-8568644.html|last=Schama |first=Simon |title=Simon Schama on Dead Certainties: 'Historians shouldn't make it up, but I did'|date=12 April 2013 |work=The Independent|access-date=2018-09-16|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/05/15/books/a-historian-enters-fiction-s-shadowy-domain.html|title=A Historian Enters Fiction's Shadowy Domain|last=Bernstein|first=Richard|work=New York Times |date=15 May 1991 |access-date=2018-09-16|language=en}}</ref>\n\nSchama mooted some possible (invented) connections between the two cases, exploring the historian's inability \"ever to reconstruct a dead world in its completeness however thorough or revealing the documentation\", and speculatively bridging \"the teasing gap separating a lived event and its subsequent narration.\" Not all readers absorbed the nuance of the title: it received a very mixed critical and academic reception. Traditional historians in particular denounced Schama's integration of fact and conjecture to produce a seamless narrative,<ref name=\"Windschuttle2000\">{{cite book|last=Windschuttle|first=Keith|authorlink=Keith Windschuttle|title=The Killing of History: How Literary Critics and Social Theorists are Murdering Our Past|year=2000|publisher=Encounter Books|location=San Francisco|isbn=1-893554-12-0|page=252|quote= [...] drawing absolute conclusions from [...] fragments of evidence}}</ref> but later assessments took a more relaxed view of the experiment.<ref name=\"Toplin1996\">{{cite book|last=Toplin|first=Robert Brent|title=History by Hollywood: the use and abuse of the American past|year=1996|publisher=University of Illinois Press|location=Urbana|isbn=0-252-06536-0|page=7|url=https://archive.org/details/historybyhollywo00topl/page/7}} \"a fascinating experiment in historical writing\".</ref>\n\nIt was an approach soon taken up by such historical writers as [[Peter Ackroyd]], [[D. J. Taylor|David Taylor]], and [[Richard Holmes (historian)|Richard Holmes]].<ref name=\"Byatt2000\">{{cite book|last=Byatt|first=A. S.|authorlink=A. S. Byatt|title=On histories and stories: selected essays|year=2000|publisher=Harvard University Press|location=Cambridge, MA|isbn=0-674-00451-5|page=[https://archive.org/details/onhistoriesstori00byat_0/page/10 10]|url=https://archive.org/details/onhistoriesstori00byat_0/page/10}}</ref>\n\nSales in hardback exceeded those of Schama's earlier works, as shown by relative rankings by amazon.com.<ref name=\"amazon DC sales 1\">[[Amazon.com|Amazon]] sales ranks (hardback versions), as at December 2010: ''Dead Certainties: Unwarranted Speculations'', 103,781; ''Citizens'', 320,762; ''The Embarrassment of Riches'', 877,177.</ref>{{original research inline|date=December 2018}}\n\nSchama's next book, ''Landscape and Memory'' (1995), focused on the relationship between physical environment and [[folk memory]], separating the components of landscape as wood, water and rock, enmeshed in the cultural consciousness of collective \"memory\" embodied in [[myth]]s, which Schama finds to be expressed outwardly in ceremony and text. More personal and idiosyncratic than ''Dead Certainties'', this book was more traditionally structured and better-defined in its approach. Despite mixed reviews, the book was a commercial success and won numerous prizes.<ref name=\"williams\">{{Cite journal|jstor=2564086|last=Williams|first=Michael|title=Review of: \"Landscape and Memory\" by Simon Schama|work=Annals of the Association of American Geographers|volume=87|issue=3|pages=564\u201365|doi=10.1111/1467-8306.t01-1-00067}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT LAM 1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/06/05/books/into-arcadia-with-simon-schama.html|title=Into Arcadia with Simon Schama|last=Gussow|first=Mel|publisher=The New York Times|date=5 June 1995|accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nPlaudits came from the art world rather than from traditional academia. Schama became [[art critic]] for ''[[The New Yorker]]'' in 1995. He held the position for three years, dovetailing his regular column with professorial duties at [[Columbia University]]; a selection of his essays on art for the magazine, chosen by Schama himself, was published in 2005 under the title ''Hang Ups''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.penguin.co.uk/books/1071523/hang-ups/|title=Hang-Ups, Essays on Painting (Mostly) by Simon Schama|website=www.penguin.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref> During this time, Schama also produced a lavishly illustrated ''Rembrandt's Eyes'', another critical and commercial success. Despite the book's title, it contrasts the biographies of [[Rembrandt van Rijn]] and [[Peter Paul Rubens]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2004/nov/06/art|title=Hang Ups by Simon Schama|last=Schama|first=Simon|date=2004-11-06|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref>\n\n===BBC===\nIn 1995, Schama wrote and presented a series called ''Landscape and Memory'' to accompany his book of the same name. Schama returned to the UK in 2000, having been commissioned by the BBC to produce a series of television documentary programmes on British history as part of their Millennium celebrations, under the title [[A History of Britain (TV series)|''A History of Britain'']].\n\nSchama wrote and presented the episodes himself, in a friendly and often jocular style with his highly characteristic delivery, and was rewarded with excellent reviews and unexpectedly high ratings. There has been, however, some irritation and criticism expressed by a group of historians about Schama's condensed recounting of the [[British Isles]]' history on this occasion, particularly by those specialising in the pre-[[Anglo-Saxons|Anglo-Saxon]] history of [[Insular Celtic]] civilisation.<ref name=\"HNN antidote 1\">{{cite web|url=http://hnn.us/comments/10421.html|title=Simon Schama Antidote|publisher=History News Network|accessdate=28 March 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060618131727/http://hnn.us/comments/10421.html|archivedate=18 June 2006}}</ref> Three series were made, totalling 15 episodes,<ref name=\"imdb AHOB 1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0273359/episodes|title=A History of Britain|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=28 March 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"cooper\"/> covering the complete span of British history up until 1965;<ref name=\"cooper\">Cooper, Barbara Roisman. ''\"A Wild Ride\" Through A History of Britain With Simon Schama.'' British Heritage 23, no. 6 (November 2002): 48. Academic Search Premier, EBSCOhost (accessed 30 April 2009)</ref> it went on to become one of the BBC's best-selling documentary series on DVD. Schama also wrote a trilogy of tie-in books for the show, which took the story up to the year 2000; there is some debate as to whether the books are the tie-in product for the TV series, or the other way around. The series also had some popularity in the United States when it was first shown on the [[History (U.S. TV channel)|History Channel]].<ref name=\"cooper\"/>\n\nIn 2001, Schama received a [[CBE]]. In 2003, he signed a new contract with the BBC and [[HarperCollins]] to produce three new books and two accompanying TV series. Worth \u00a33 million (around US$5.3m), it represents the biggest advance deal ever for a TV historian. The first result of the deal was a book and TV show entitled ''[[Rough Crossings]]: Britain, the Slaves and the American Revolution'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/sep/03/featuresreviews.guardianreview2|title=Review: Rough Crossings by Simon Schama|last=Walvin|first=James|date=2005-09-03|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref> dealing in particular with the proclamation issued during the [[Revolutionary War (United States)|Revolutionary War]] by [[Lord Dunmore]] offering slaves from rebel plantations freedom in return for service to the crown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/sep/25/historybooks.features|title=Observer review: Rough Crossings by Simon Schama|last=Butterworth|first=Alex|date=2005-09-24|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 the BBC broadcast a new TV series, ''[[Simon Schama's Power of Art]]'' which, with an accompanying book, was presented and written by Schama. It marks a return to art history for him, treating eight artists through eight key works: [[Caravaggio]]'s [[:Image:Michelangelo Caravaggio 018.jpg|''David with the Head of Goliath'']], [[Bernini]]'s ''[[Ecstasy of St Theresa]]'', [[Rembrandt]]'s [[The Conspiracy of Claudius Civilis|''Conspiracy of Claudius Civilis'']], [[Jacques-Louis David]]'s [[:Image:Death of Marat by David.jpg|''The Death of Marat'']], [[J. M. W. Turner]]'s ''[[The Slave Ship]]'', [[Vincent van Gogh]]'s ''[[Wheat Field with Crows]]'', [[Picasso]]'s ''[[:Guernica (painting)|Guernica]]'' and [[Mark Rothko]]'s ''Seagram Murals''.<ref name=\"BBC POA 1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/powerofart|title=Simon Schama's Power of Art|work=[[BBC Two]]|publisher=BBC|accessdate=28 March 2007}}</ref> It was also shown on [[PBS]] in the United States.<ref name=\"nalley\">Nalley, Richard. \"Simon Schama's Power of Art.\" Forbes 180 (18 September 2007): 165\u2013165. Academic Search Premier, EBSCOhost (accessed 30 April 2009).</ref>\n\nIn October 2008, on the eve of the [[2008 United States presidential election|presidential election won by Barack Obama]], the BBC broadcast a four-part television series called ''[[The American Future: A History]]'' presented and written by Schama. In March 2009, Schama presented a [[BBC Radio 4]] show entitled ''Baseball and Me'', both exploring the history of the game and describing his own personal support of the [[Boston Red Sox]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00hyjl4/episodes/guide|title=BBC Radio 4 Extra - Simon Schama - Baseball and Me - Episode guide|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Schama presented a series of ten talks for the [[BBC Radio 4]] series ''A Point of View'':\n* ''Why We Like Tough Guys in Politics'': When times are hard people seem to prefer tough leaders.\n* ''Singing in the Rain'': Schama looks forward to spring with personal reflections on the changing seasons.\n* ''At the Heart of the Matter'': The politics surrounding President [[Barack Obama]]'s healthcare reforms.\n* ''The Gift of the Gab'': The history of political rhetoric and the power during election campaigns of televised debates.\n* ''Behold, Newstralia!'': Celebrates the distinctive history and culture of [[New Zealand]] and regrets any renewed talk of joining forces with Australia.\n* ''A Welcome Slice of American Pie'': Reflection on the quality of American food and eating habits.\n* ''The Drama of Politics'': The timeless drama of [[British politics]].\n* ''When Money is Just an Illusion'': Reflection on the meaning of money as represented by coins and notes and in art.\n* ''Hearts of Oak'': Reflection on the significance of one of the sights that will greet new MPs in the chamber of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] \u2013 the panelling made of solid oak.\n* ''Britain's New Politics'': Reflection on the [[2010 United Kingdom general election]], favourably comparing the British system for a swift handover of power to the cumbersome American one.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00rz0kn|title=A welcome slice of American pie, A Point of View - BBC Radio 4|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 the BBC commissioned Simon Schama to write and present a five-part series called ''A History of the Jews'' for [[BBC Two]] for transmission in 2012,<ref name=\"BBC AHOTJ 1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2011/02_february/24/schama.shtml|title=Simon Schama to present The History of the Jews on BBC Two|publisher=BBC|date=2 February 2011}}</ref> The title became ''[[The Story of the Jews]]'' and broadcast was delayed until September 2013.<ref name=\"BBC progs 2013 1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0392pzx|title=The Story of the Jews|work=[[BBC Programmes]]|publisher=BBC Two|accessdate=10 September 2013}}</ref> Writing in ''[[The Observer]]'', Andrew Anthony called it \"an astonishing achievement, a TV landmark.\"<ref name=\"Anthony\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2013/sep/28/observer-profile-simon-schama|title=Simon Schama: a man always making history|work=[[The Observer]]|date=28 September 2013|accessdate=7 October 2013|author=Anthony, Andrew}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Simon Schama wrote and presented five of the nine episodes of ''[[Civilisations (TV series)|Civilisations]]'', a reboot of the [[Civilisation (TV series)|1969 series]] by [[Kenneth Clark]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/GThNCvQtxsgJfJrxCxFJb2/civilisations-masterworks-of-beauty-and-ingenuity|title=Civilisations: Masterworks of beauty and ingenuity|website=BBC|access-date=16 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSchama is Jewish. He is married to Virginia Papaioannou, a geneticist from California; they have two children, Chloe and Gabriel.<ref name=\"telegraph the american future \">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/7912996/Simon-Schama-Could-I-have-multiple-personality-disorder.html|title=Simon Schama: Could I have multiple personality disorder?|publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=15 February 2017}}</ref> As of 2014, he resides in [[Briarcliff Manor, New York]].<ref name=\"Briarcliff\">{{cite news|last=Lombroso|first=Linda|title=Briarcliff historian tells PBS' 'The Story of the Jews'|url=http://www.lohud.com/story/entertainment/2014/03/24/story-jews-simon-schama/6835897/|accessdate=2 September 2014|newspaper=The Journal News|date=24 March 2014}}</ref> Schama is a [[Tottenham Hotspur]] supporter.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Schama |first1=Simon |title=The Yid Army\u2019s chants turn anti-semitism into kitsch banter |url=https://www.ft.com/content/c3fbd9e6-21e2-11e3-9b55-00144feab7de |website=Financial Times}}</ref>\n\n===Politics===\nIn 2010, Schama was a financial donor to [[Oona King]]'s unsuccessful campaign to become [[Mayor of London]].<ref name=\"guardian 2012 elections 1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/aug/13/labour-leadership-donations-miliband-burnham-balls|location=London|work=The Guardian|title=David Miliband hits it rich in leadership race as stars back Burnham and Balls|first=Michael|last=White|date=13 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, Schama was one of 200 public figures who were signatories to a letter to ''[[The Guardian]]'' expressing their hope that Scotland would vote to remain part of the United Kingdom in September's [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|referendum on that issue]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/aug/07/celebrities-open-letter-scotland-independence-full-text |title=Celebrities' open letter to Scotland \u2013 full text and list of signatories |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=7 August 2014 |accessdate=26 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, Schama joined [[Simon Sebag Montefiore]] and [[Howard Jacobson]] in writing a letter to ''[[The Times]]'' about their concern over [[Antisemitism in the UK Labour Party|antisemitism in the Labour Party]] under [[Jeremy Corbyn]]'s leadership, with particular reference to a growth in [[Anti-Zionism]] and its \"antisemitic characteristics\". Schama and Sebag Montefiore have both written historical works about Israel, while Jacobson has written regularly about Israel and the UK Jewish community in his newspaper columns.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/simon-schama-simon-sebag-montefiore-and-howard-jacobson-unite-to-condemn-labour-antisemitism-1.447432 |title=Schama, Sebag-Montefiore and Jacobson unite to condemn Labour antisemitism |work=The Jewish Chronicle | first=Daniel | last=Sugarman | date=6 November 2017 |accessdate=2 May 2018}}</ref> Schama made a further criticism of the party in July 2019, when he joined other leading Jewish figures in saying, in a letter to ''The Guardian'', that the crisis was \"a taint of international and historic shame\" and that trust in the party was \"fractured beyond repair\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/14/jewish-intellectuals-express-outrage-over-labours-handling-of-antisemitism-crisis |title=Jewish figures rail against Labour\u2019s handling of antisemitism charges |work=The Guardian | first=Stefan | last=Boscia | date=14 July 2019 |accessdate=24 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Israel====\nSchama was critical of a call by British novelist [[John Berger]] for an [[Academic boycott of Israel|academic boycott of Israel]] over its policies towards the [[Palestinians]]. Writing in ''[[The Guardian]]'' in a 2006 article co-authored with [[Anthony Julius]], Schama compared Berger's academic boycott to policies adopted by [[Nazi Germany]], saying: \"This is not the first boycott call directed at [[Jews]]. On 1 April 1933, only weeks after he came to power, [[Adolf Hitler|Hitler]] ordered a [[Nazi boycott of Jewish businesses| boycott of Jewish shops, banks, offices and department stores]].\"<ref name=\"guardian 2006 boycott 1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2006/dec/22/bergerboycott|title=John Berger is wrong|author1=Simon Schama|author2=Anthony Julius|publisher=The Guardian|date=22 December 2006|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 on the BBC, Schama debated with [[Vivienne Westwood]] the morality of Israel's actions in the [[2006 Lebanon War|Israel-Lebanon War]].<ref name=\"bbc2006\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/this_week/5210018.stm|title=This Week \u2013 Simon Schama & Vivienne Westwood|work=[[This Week (BBC TV series)|This Week]]|publisher=BBC|date=24 July 2006|accessdate=}}</ref> He described Israel's bombing of Lebanese city centres as unhelpful to Israel's attempt to \"get rid of\" Hezbollah.<ref name=\"bbc2006\"/> He said: \"Of course the spectacle and suffering makes us grieve. Who wouldn't grieve? But it's not enough to do that. We've got to understand. You've even got to understand Israel's point of view.\"<ref name=\"bbc2006\"/>\n\n====United States====\nSchama was a supporter of President [[Barack Obama]]<ref name=\"guardian obama support 1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/aug/30/barackobama.democrats20081|title=In its severity and fury, this was Obama at his most powerful and moving|last=Schama|first=Simon|date=30 August 2008|work=[[The Guardian]]|page=34|accessdate=5 November 2008|location=London}}</ref> and a critic of [[George W. Bush]].<ref name=\"guardian bush critic 1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/nov/03/george-bush-legacy-dubya|title=Nowhere man: a farewell to Dubya, all-time loser in presidential history|last=Schama|first=Simon|date=3 November 2008|work=[[The Guardian]]|pages=1\u20132|accessdate=5 November 2008|location=London}}</ref> He appeared on the BBC's coverage of the [[2008 United States presidential election|2008 US presidential election]], clashing with [[John R. Bolton|John Bolton]].<ref name=\"ET 2008 schama PE 1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/news/display.var.2465762.0.road_to_the_white_house.php |title=Road to the White House |date=5 November 2008 |work=[[The Evening Times]] |accessdate=5 November 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081108041640/http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/news/display.var.2465762.0.road_to_the_white_house.php |archivedate=8 November 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Prizes and other honours==\n* 1977: [[Wolfson History Prize]], for ''Patriots and Liberators''\n* 1977: [[Leo Gershoy Award]], for ''Patriots and Liberators''\n* 1987: [[New York Times Best Books of the Year|''New York Times'' Best Books of the Year]], for ''The Embarrassment of Riches''\n* 1989: ''New York Times'' Best Books of the Year, for ''Citizens: A Chronicle of the French Revolution''\n* 1989: ''Yorkshire Post'' Book Award, for ''Citizens: A Chronicle of the French Revolution''\n* 1990: [[NCR Book Award]], for ''Citizens: A Chronicle of the French Revolution''\n* 1992: [[American Academy of Arts and Letters]] Award for Literature\n* 1995: Elected to Honorary Fellowship, Christ's College, Cambridge\n* 1996: Lionel Trilling Book Award, for ''Landscape and Memory''\n* 1996: [[National Magazine Awards]], for critical essays in [[The New Yorker]]\n* 1996: [[WH Smith Literary Award]], for ''Landscape and Memory''\n* 2001: [[St. Louis Literary Award]] from the [[Saint Louis University]] Library Associates<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slu.edu/libraries/associates/award.html|title=Saint Louis Literary Award - Saint Louis University|website=www.slu.edu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://lib.slu.edu/about/associates/literary-award/schama|title=Saint Louis University Library Associates Announce Winner of 2001 Literary Award|author=Saint Louis University Library Associates|accessdate=25 July 2016}}</ref>\n* 2001: Broadcasting Press Guild Writer's Award, for ''A History of Britain''\n* 2001: Nominated for BAFTA Huw Wheldon Award for Specialised Programme or Series (Arts, History, Religion and Science), for ''A History of Britain''<ref name=\"Wheldon\">{{cite web | url=http://awards.bafta.org/keyword-search?keywords=Huw+Wheldon+Award | title=BAFTA Awards | publisher=British Academy of Film and Television Arts | accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>\n* 2002: Nominated for BAFTA Richard Dimbleby Award for the Best Presenter (Factual, Features and News), for ''A History of Britain''\n* 2003: Nominated for Outstanding Individual Achievement in a Craft: Writing [[Emmy Award]] for ''The Two Winstons'', an episode of ''A History of Britain''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0769988/awards|title=Simon Schama - Awards|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n* 2006: [[National Book Critics Circle Award]] for Non-fiction winner, for ''Rough Crossings''<ref name=\"NYT 2006 NBCCA 1\">Bosman, Julie. \"National Briefing | Arts: National Book Critics Circle Winners\", ''New York Times'' (9 March 2007): 20. Academic Search Premier; accessed 1 May 2009.</ref>\n* 2006: Hessell-Tiltman Prize Shortlist, for ''Rough Crossings''\n* 2007: [[International Emmy Award]], for ''Bernini'', an episode of ''Simon Schama's Power of Art''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.columbia.edu/cu/news/07/11/schama.html|title=Professor Schama Wins International Emmy for Power of Art|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n* 2007: Nominated for BAFTA Huw Wheldon Award for Specialised Factual Programme or Series, for ''Simon Schama's Power of Art''\n* 2008: ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''{{'}}s 110 Best Books: The Perfect Library, for ''Citizens: A Chronicle of the French Revolution''\n* 2011: Kenyon Review Award for Literary Achievement<ref>{{cite web|title=Kenyon Review for Literary Achievement|url=https://www.kenyonreview.org/programs/kenyon-review-award-for-literary-achievement/simon-schama|website=kenyonreview.org|accessdate=16 June 2018}}</ref> \n* 2015: [[Corresponding Fellow of the British Academy|Corresponding Fellow]] of the [[British Academy]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britac.ac.uk/news/british-academy-fellowship-reaches-1000-42-new-uk-fellows-are-welcomed|title=British Academy Fellowship reaches 1,000 as 42 new UK Fellows are welcomed|date=16 July 2015|access-date=16 June 2018}}</ref>\n* 2015: [[Feltrinelli Prize]] for History\n* 2017: [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Literature]]<ref>Natasha Onwuemezi, [http://www.thebookseller.com/news/syal-and-mcdermid-named-new-rsl-fellows-564396 \"Rankin, McDermid and Levy named new RSL fellows\"], ''[[The Bookseller]]'', 7 June 2017; accessdate 16 June 2018.</ref>\n* [[2018 Birthday Honours|2018]]: [[Knight Bachelor]], for services to history\n\n==Bibliography==\n;Books\n* ''Patriots and Liberators: Revolution in the Netherlands 1780\u20131813'' (1977)\n* ''Two Rothschilds and the Land of Israel'' (1978)\n* ''[[The Embarrassment of Riches|The Embarrassment of Riches: An Interpretation of Dutch Culture in the Golden Age]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Citizens: A Chronicle of the French Revolution]]'' (1989)<ref name=\"snowman\"/>\n* ''Dead Certainties: Unwarranted Speculations'' (1991, {{ISBN|0394222202}})\n* ''Landscape and Memory'' (1995, {{ISBN|0679402551}})<ref name=\"williams\"/><ref name=\"binstock\">{{Cite journal|jstor=3051386  |last=Binstock |first=Benjamin |title=eRembrandt's Eyes by Simon Schama |work=The Art Bulletin |volume= 82| issue =  2 (Jun. 2000) |pages= 361\u2013366 }}</ref>\n* ''Rembrandt's Eyes'' (1999, {{ISBN|0676593925}})<ref name=\"binstock\"/>\n* ''[[A History of Britain (book)|A History of Britain]]'' Vol. I (2000, {{ISBN| 0-563-48714-3}})\n* ''A History of Britain'' Vol. II (2001, {{ISBN|0-563-48718-6}})\n* ''A History of Britain'' Vol. III (2002, {{ISBN|0-563-48719-4}})\n* ''Hang Ups: Essays on Art'' (2004, {{ISBN|0563521732}})\n* ''[[Rough Crossings]]'' (2005, {{ISBN|0-06-053916-X}})\n* ''Simon Schama's Power of Art'' (2006, {{ISBN|0-06-117610-9}})<ref name=\"nalley\"/>\n* ''The American Future: A History'' (2009, {{ISBN|0-06-053923-2}})\n* ''Scribble, Scribble, Scribble: Writing on Politics, Ice Cream, Churchill and My Mother'' (2011, {{ISBN|978-0062009869}})\n* ''The Story of the Jews, Volume I: Finding the Words, 1000 BCE\u20131492 CE'' (2013, [[Bodley Head]],  {{ISBN|9781847921321}})<ref name=\"Johnson\">{{cite news | url=http://www.spectator.co.uk/books/9024421/the-story-of-the-jews-by-simon-schama-review/ | title=The Story of the Jews, by Simon Schama \u2013 review | work=[[The Spectator]] | date=21 September 2013 | accessdate=7 October 2013 | author=Johnson, Paul}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Face of Britain (Schama book)|The Face of Britain]]: The Nation through Its Portraits'' (2015, {{ISBN|9780241963715}})\n* ''Belonging: The Story of the Jews 1492\u20131900'', Volume II of the trilogy (2017, [[Bodley Head]],  {{ISBN|9781847922809}})<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2017/oct/06/simon-schama-interview-jewish-history-belonging-jonathan-freedland | title=Simon Schama: finding the light in the darkness of the Jewish story \u2013 review | work=[[The Guardian]] | date=6 October 2017 | accessdate=24 October 2017 | author=Freedland, Jonathan}}</ref>\n\n;Television documentaries\n* ''Landscape and Memory'' (1995), in five parts\n* ''Rembrandt: The Public Eye and the Private Gaze'' (1995)\n* ''[[A History of Britain (TV series)|A History of Britain by Simon Schama]]'' \u2013 BBC (2000), in 15 parts\n* ''Murder at Harvard'' \u2013 PBS (2003)\n* ''[[Rough Crossings]]'' \u2013 BBC (2005)\n* ''[[Simon Schama's Power of Art]]'' \u2013 BBC (2006), in eight parts\n* ''[[The American Future: A History]]'' \u2013 BBC (2008), in four parts\n* ''Simon Schama's John Donne'' \u2013 BBC (2009)\n* ''Simon Schama's: Obama's America'' \u2013 BBC (2009)\n* ''Simon Schama's Shakespeare'' \u2013 BBC (2012)\n* ''[[The Story of the Jews]]'' \u2013 BBC (2013), in five parts\n* ''Schama on Rembrandt: Masterpieces of the Late Years'' \u2013 BBC (2014)\n* ''The Face of Britain by Simon Schama'' \u2013 BBC (2015), in five parts\n* ''[[Civilisations (TV series)|Civilisations]]'' \u2013 BBC (2018), five of nine parts\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.columbia.edu/cu/arthistory/html/dept_faculty_schama.html Columbia Art History faculty page]\n* {{C-SPAN|Simon Schama}}\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/culture/simon-schama Simon Schama | Culture | The Guardian]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/profile/simonschama Simon Schama | The Guardian]\n*[https://www.newstatesman.com/node/152276 Simon Schama | New Statesman]\n*[https://www.spectator.co.uk/tag/simon-schama/ Simon Schama] on ''[[The Spectator]]''\n\n{{Wolfson History Prize Winners}}\n{{FBA 2015}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schama, Simon}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century English historians]]\n[[Category:21st-century English historians]]\n[[Category:21st-century English writers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Christ's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:British expatriate academics in the United States]]\n[[Category:Columbia University faculty]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Corresponding Fellows of the British Academy]]\n[[Category:English art historians]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:English Jews]]\n[[Category:English people of Lithuanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Romanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Turkish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:English television presenters]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Brasenose College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Christ's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n[[Category:Harvard University faculty]]\n[[Category:Historians of the Dutch Republic]]\n[[Category:Historians of the French Revolution]]\n[[Category:Historians of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Jewish historians]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:NCR Book Award winners]]\n[[Category:People educated at Haberdashers' Aske's Boys' School]]\n[[Category:People from Briarcliff Manor, New York]]\n[[Category:People from Marylebone]]\n[[Category:People from Southend-on-Sea]]\n[[Category:Rembrandt scholars]]\n[[Category:Scholars of Dutch art]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name        = Sir Simon Schama\n| honorific_suffix = [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]], [[Fellow of the British Academy|FBA]], [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Literature|FRSL]]\n| image       = Simon Schama FT.jpg\n| image_size  = 200px\n| caption     = Schama in 2013\n| birth_name  = Simon Michael Schama\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1945|02|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Marylebone, London]], England\n| residence   = [[Briarcliff Manor, New York]], U.S.\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| occupation  = Academic, [[art history|art historian]]\n| education   = [[Haberdashers' Aske's Boys' School]]\n| alma_mater  = [[Christ's College, Cambridge]]\n| spouse      = Virginia Papaioannou\n| children    = 2\n| awards      = [[Wolfson History Prize]]<br />[[Leo Gershoy Award]]<br />[[Fellow of the Royal Society of Literature]]\n| module      = <center>{{Listen|embed=yes|filename=Simon Schama BBC Radio4 Start the Week 30 December 2013 b03mcmwx.flac|title=<center>Simon Schama's voice</center>|type=speech|description=<center>[[:File:Simon Schama BBC Radio4 Start the Week 30 December 2013 b03mcmwx.flac|Recorded December 2013]] from the BBC Radio 4 programme ''[[Start the Week]]''</center>}}</center>\n}}\n\n'''Sir Simon Michael Schama''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CBE|FBA|FRSL}} ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0283|\u00e6|m|\u0259}}; born 13 February 1945) is an English historian specialising in [[art history]], [[Dutch history]], Jewish history and [[French history]].<ref name=\"snowman\"/> He is a University Professor of History and Art History at [[Columbia University]], New York.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.culpa.info/professors/568|title=Columbia student reviews of Schama's teaching|date=2005|website=CULPA}}</ref>\n\nHe first came to public attention with his history of the [[French Revolution]] titled ''[[Citizens: A Chronicle of the French Revolution|Citizens]]'', published in 1989.<ref name=\"snowman\"/> In the United Kingdom, he is perhaps best known for writing and hosting the 15-part BBC television documentary series ''[[Simon Schama's A History of Britain|A History of Britain]]'' broadcast between 2000 and 2002.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b008qpzn/episodes/guide|title=BBC Two - A History of Britain by Simon Schama - Episode guide|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2000/oct/01/historybooks.robertmccrum|title=Observer review: A History of Britain by Simon Schama|last=McCrum|first=Robert|date=2000-09-30|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref> Schama was [[knighted]] in the [[2018 Queen's Birthday Honours]] List.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/62310/supplement/B1 |title=Honours list|date=2018 |website= www.thegazette.co.uk|publisher=|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nSchama was born in [[Marylebone]], London.<ref name=\"snowman\">{{cite journal | last1 = Snowman | first1 = Daniel | author1-link = Daniel Snowman | year = 2004 | title = Simon Schama | journal = History Today | volume = 54 | issue = 7| pages = 34\u201336 | url = https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-0-230-59997-0_24 }}</ref><ref name=\"JC background 1\">{{cite news|url=http://website.thejc.com/home.aspx?AId=46437&ATypeId=1&search=true2&srchtxt=1&srchhead=1&srchauthor=1&srchsandp=1&scsrch=0|author= Silverstone, Ben|title=Schama's art of making history|work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]|accessdate=23 July 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005064559/http://website.thejc.com/home.aspx?AId=46437&ATypeId=1&search=true2&srchtxt=1&srchhead=1&srchauthor=1&srchsandp=1&scsrch=0|archivedate=5 October 2011}}</ref> His mother, Gertie (n\u00e9e Steinberg), was from an [[Ashkenazi]] Jewish family (from [[Kaunas]], present-day [[Lithuania]]), and his father, Arthur Schama, was of [[Sephardi]] Jewish background (from Smyrna, present-day [[\u0130zmir]] in Turkey), later moving through Moldova and Romania.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishtelegraph.com/prof_217.html|last=Wachmann |first=Doreen |title=Profile: Biblical Tales Gave Schama his First Taste for History |date=2013 |work=[[Jewish Telegraph]]|publisher=Jewishtelegraph.com|accessdate=26 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejc.com/112351/simon-schama-interview|title=Simon Schama Interview &#124; The Jewish Chronicle|publisher=Thejc.com|date=12 October 2013|accessdate=26 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the mid-1940s, the family moved to [[Southend-on-Sea]] in Essex before moving back to London. In 1956, Schama won a scholarship to the private [[Haberdashers' Aske's Boys' School]] in [[Cricklewood]], (from 1961 [[Elstree]], Hertfordshire). He then studied history at [[Christ's College, Cambridge]], where he was taught by [[John H. Plumb]]. He graduated from the [[University of Cambridge]] with a [[British undergraduate degree classification#Variations of first-class honours|Starred First]] in 1966.<ref name=\"snowman\"/>\n\n==Career==\nSchama worked for short periods as a lecturer in history at Cambridge, where he was a Fellow and Director of Studies in History at [[Christ's College, Cambridge |Christ's College]]. He then taught for some time at [[Oxford University|Oxford]], where he was made a Fellow of [[Brasenose College]] in 1976, specialising in the [[French Revolution]].<ref name=\"snowman\"/>\n\nAt this time, Schama wrote his first book, ''Patriots and Liberators'', which won the [[Wolfson History Prize]]. The book was originally intended as a study of the French Revolution, but as published in 1977, it focused on the effect of the ''[[Patriottentijd]]'' revolution of the 1780s in the Netherlands, and its [[Batavian Republic|aftermath]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.harpercollins.co.uk/9780006861560/patriots-and-liberators/|title=Patriots and Liberators by Simon Schama - Paperback {{!}} HarperCollins|work=HarperCollins UK|access-date=2018-09-16|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/1999/oct/16/books.guardianreview10|title=History, his way|date=1999-10-16|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref>\n\nHis second book, ''Two Rothschilds and the Land of Israel'' (1978), is a study of the [[Zionism|Zionist]] aims of [[Edmond James de Rothschild|Edmond]] and [[James Armand de Rothschild|James Rothschild]].\n\n===In the United States===\n[[File:Simon Schama at The Strand by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|Schama at New York City's [[Strand Bookstore]] in 2006.]]\nIn 1980, Schama took up a chair at [[Harvard University]]. His next book, ''The Embarrassment of Riches'' (1987), again focused on Dutch history.<ref name=\"TEOR publication 1\">Daniel, M., and S. Steinberg. \"Simon Schama.\" Publishers Weekly 238, No. 22 (17 May 1991): 46. Academic Search Premier, EBSCOhost (accessed 30 April 2009).</ref> Schama interpreted the ambivalences that informed the [[Dutch Golden Age]] of the 17th century, held in balance between the conflicting imperatives, to live richly and with power, or to live a godly life. The iconographic evidence that Schama draws upon, in 317 illustrations, of emblems and propaganda that defined Dutch character, prefigured his expansion in the 1990s as a commentator on art and visual culture.<ref name=\"TEOR commentator 1\">Adams, Julia; Stoler, Ann (November 1988). \"The Embarrassment of Riches: An Interpretation of Dutch Culture in the Golden Age, by Simon Schama\" (review). ''[[Contemporary Sociology]]''. '''17'''.6: 760\u201362. \"He provides a reading of cultural tints and social textures at a level of visual detail that is usually reserved for art history.\" {{doi|10.2307/2073570}}</ref>\n\n''Citizens'' (1989), written at speed to a publisher's commission, saw the publication of his long-awaited study of the [[French Revolution]], and won the 1990 [[NCR Book Award]]. Its view that the violence of the Terror was inherent from the start of the Revolution, however, has received serious negative criticism.<ref name=\"snowman\"/><ref name=\"Citizens 1989 1\">Notably in Timothy Tackett, \"Interpreting the Terror\" ''French Historical Studies'' '''24'''.4 (Autumn 2001:569\u2013578); Tackett's view of swiftly evolving revolution in his [[prosopography]] of the deputies, ''Becoming a Revolutionary: The Deputies of the French National Assembly and the Emergence of a Revolutionary Culture, 1789\u20131790'' (Princeton University Press) 1996, was not fundamentally at variance with Schama.</ref>\n\nSchama appeared as an on-screen expert in [[Michael Wood (historian)|Michael Wood]]'s 1989 PBS series, ''Art of the Western World'' as a presenting art historian, commenting on paintings by [[Diego Vel\u00e1zquez]], [[Rembrandt]], and [[Johannes Vermeer]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Art of the Western World (TV Series 1989\u2013 )|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0363314/fullcredits|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, he published ''Dead Certainties (Unwarranted Speculations)'',<ref name=\"Halttunen DC published 1\">{{Cite journal|jstor=2080071|last=Halttunen|first=Karen|title=Review of \"Dead Certainties (Unwarranted Speculations) by Simon Schama|work=The Journal of American History|volume=79| issue =  2 |date=September 1992|page=631}}</ref> a relatively slender work of unusual structure and point-of-view in that it looked at two widely reported deaths a hundred years apart, that of British Army General [[James Wolfe]] in 1759 \u2013 and the famous 1770 [[The Death of General Wolfe|painting depicting the event]] by [[Benjamin West]] \u2013 and that of [[George Parkman]], murdered uncle of the better known 19th-century American historian [[Francis Parkman]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/simon-schama-on-dead-certainties-historians-shouldnt-make-it-up-but-i-did-8568644.html|last=Schama |first=Simon |title=Simon Schama on Dead Certainties: 'Historians shouldn't make it up, but I did'|date=12 April 2013 |work=The Independent|access-date=2018-09-16|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/05/15/books/a-historian-enters-fiction-s-shadowy-domain.html|title=A Historian Enters Fiction's Shadowy Domain|last=Bernstein|first=Richard|work=New York Times |date=15 May 1991 |access-date=2018-09-16|language=en}}</ref>\n\nSchama mooted some possible (invented) connections between the two cases, exploring the historian's inability \"ever to reconstruct a dead world in its completeness however thorough or revealing the documentation\", and speculatively bridging \"the teasing gap separating a lived event and its subsequent narration.\" Not all readers absorbed the nuance of the title: it received a very mixed critical and academic reception. Traditional historians in particular denounced Schama's integration of fact and conjecture to produce a seamless narrative,<ref name=\"Windschuttle2000\">{{cite book|last=Windschuttle|first=Keith|authorlink=Keith Windschuttle|title=The Killing of History: How Literary Critics and Social Theorists are Murdering Our Past|year=2000|publisher=Encounter Books|location=San Francisco|isbn=1-893554-12-0|page=252|quote= [...] drawing absolute conclusions from [...] fragments of evidence}}</ref> but later assessments took a more relaxed view of the experiment.<ref name=\"Toplin1996\">{{cite book|last=Toplin|first=Robert Brent|title=History by Hollywood: the use and abuse of the American past|year=1996|publisher=University of Illinois Press|location=Urbana|isbn=0-252-06536-0|page=7|url=https://archive.org/details/historybyhollywo00topl/page/7}} \"a fascinating experiment in historical writing\".</ref>\n\nIt was an approach soon taken up by such historical writers as [[Peter Ackroyd]], [[D. J. Taylor|David Taylor]], and [[Richard Holmes (historian)|Richard Holmes]].<ref name=\"Byatt2000\">{{cite book|last=Byatt|first=A. S.|authorlink=A. S. Byatt|title=On histories and stories: selected essays|year=2000|publisher=Harvard University Press|location=Cambridge, MA|isbn=0-674-00451-5|page=[https://archive.org/details/onhistoriesstori00byat_0/page/10 10]|url=https://archive.org/details/onhistoriesstori00byat_0/page/10}}</ref>\n\nSales in hardback exceeded those of Schama's earlier works, as shown by relative rankings by amazon.com.<ref name=\"amazon DC sales 1\">[[Amazon.com|Amazon]] sales ranks (hardback versions), as at December 2010: ''Dead Certainties: Unwarranted Speculations'', 103,781; ''Citizens'', 320,762; ''The Embarrassment of Riches'', 877,177.</ref>{{original research inline|date=December 2018}}\n\nSchama's next book, ''Landscape and Memory'' (1995), focused on the relationship between physical environment and [[folk memory]], separating the components of landscape as wood, water and rock, enmeshed in the cultural consciousness of collective \"memory\" embodied in [[myth]]s, which Schama finds to be expressed outwardly in ceremony and text. More personal and idiosyncratic than ''Dead Certainties'', this book was more traditionally structured and better-defined in its approach. Despite mixed reviews, the book was a commercial success and won numerous prizes.<ref name=\"williams\">{{Cite journal|jstor=2564086|last=Williams|first=Michael|title=Review of: \"Landscape and Memory\" by Simon Schama|work=Annals of the Association of American Geographers|volume=87|issue=3|pages=564\u201365|doi=10.1111/1467-8306.t01-1-00067}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT LAM 1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/06/05/books/into-arcadia-with-simon-schama.html|title=Into Arcadia with Simon Schama|last=Gussow|first=Mel|publisher=The New York Times|date=5 June 1995|accessdate=19 April 2013}}</ref>\n\nPlaudits came from the art world rather than from traditional academia. Schama became [[art critic]] for ''[[The New Yorker]]'' in 1995. He held the position for three years, dovetailing his regular column with professorial duties at [[Columbia University]]; a selection of his essays on art for the magazine, chosen by Schama himself, was published in 2005 under the title ''Hang Ups''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.penguin.co.uk/books/1071523/hang-ups/|title=Hang-Ups, Essays on Painting (Mostly) by Simon Schama|website=www.penguin.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref> During this time, Schama also produced a lavishly illustrated ''Rembrandt's Eyes'', another critical and commercial success. Despite the book's title, it contrasts the biographies of [[Rembrandt van Rijn]] and [[Peter Paul Rubens]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2004/nov/06/art|title=Hang Ups by Simon Schama|last=Schama|first=Simon|date=2004-11-06|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref>\n\n===BBC===\nIn 1995, Schama wrote and presented a series called ''Landscape and Memory'' to accompany his book of the same name. Schama returned to the UK in 2000, having been commissioned by the BBC to produce a series of television documentary programmes on British history as part of their Millennium celebrations, under the title [[A History of Britain (TV series)|''A History of Britain'']].\n\nSchama wrote and presented the episodes himself, in a friendly and often jocular style with his highly characteristic delivery, and was rewarded with excellent reviews and unexpectedly high ratings. There has been, however, some irritation and criticism expressed by a group of historians about Schama's condensed recounting of the [[British Isles]]' history on this occasion, particularly by those specialising in the pre-[[Anglo-Saxons|Anglo-Saxon]] history of [[Insular Celtic]] civilisation.<ref name=\"HNN antidote 1\">{{cite web|url=http://hnn.us/comments/10421.html|title=Simon Schama Antidote|publisher=History News Network|accessdate=28 March 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060618131727/http://hnn.us/comments/10421.html|archivedate=18 June 2006}}</ref> Three series were made, totalling 15 episodes,<ref name=\"imdb AHOB 1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0273359/episodes|title=A History of Britain|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=28 March 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"cooper\"/> covering the complete span of British history up until 1965;<ref name=\"cooper\">Cooper, Barbara Roisman. ''\"A Wild Ride\" Through A History of Britain With Simon Schama.'' British Heritage 23, no. 6 (November 2002): 48. Academic Search Premier, EBSCOhost (accessed 30 April 2009)</ref> it went on to become one of the BBC's best-selling documentary series on DVD. Schama also wrote a trilogy of tie-in books for the show, which took the story up to the year 2000; there is some debate as to whether the books are the tie-in product for the TV series, or the other way around. The series also had some popularity in the United States when it was first shown on the [[History (U.S. TV channel)|History Channel]].<ref name=\"cooper\"/>\n\nIn 2001, Schama received a [[CBE]]. In 2003, he signed a new contract with the BBC and [[HarperCollins]] to produce three new books and two accompanying TV series. Worth \u00a33 million (around US$5.3m), it represents the biggest advance deal ever for a TV historian. The first result of the deal was a book and TV show entitled ''[[Rough Crossings]]: Britain, the Slaves and the American Revolution'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/sep/03/featuresreviews.guardianreview2|title=Review: Rough Crossings by Simon Schama|last=Walvin|first=James|date=2005-09-03|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref> dealing in particular with the proclamation issued during the [[Revolutionary War (United States)|Revolutionary War]] by [[Lord Dunmore]] offering slaves from rebel plantations freedom in return for service to the crown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/sep/25/historybooks.features|title=Observer review: Rough Crossings by Simon Schama|last=Butterworth|first=Alex|date=2005-09-24|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 the BBC broadcast a new TV series, ''[[Simon Schama's Power of Art]]'' which, with an accompanying book, was presented and written by Schama. It marks a return to art history for him, treating eight artists through eight key works: [[Caravaggio]]'s [[:Image:Michelangelo Caravaggio 018.jpg|''David with the Head of Goliath'']], [[Bernini]]'s ''[[Ecstasy of St Theresa]]'', [[Rembrandt]]'s [[The Conspiracy of Claudius Civilis|''Conspiracy of Claudius Civilis'']], [[Jacques-Louis David]]'s [[:Image:Death of Marat by David.jpg|''The Death of Marat'']], [[J. M. W. Turner]]'s ''[[The Slave Ship]]'', [[Vincent van Gogh]]'s ''[[Wheat Field with Crows]]'', [[Picasso]]'s ''[[:Guernica (painting)|Guernica]]'' and [[Mark Rothko]]'s ''Seagram Murals''.<ref name=\"BBC POA 1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/arts/powerofart|title=Simon Schama's Power of Art|work=[[BBC Two]]|publisher=BBC|accessdate=28 March 2007}}</ref> It was also shown on [[PBS]] in the United States.<ref name=\"nalley\">Nalley, Richard. \"Simon Schama's Power of Art.\" Forbes 180 (18 September 2007): 165\u2013165. Academic Search Premier, EBSCOhost (accessed 30 April 2009).</ref>\n\nIn October 2008, on the eve of the [[2008 United States presidential election|presidential election won by Barack Obama]], the BBC broadcast a four-part television series called ''[[The American Future: A History]]'' presented and written by Schama. In March 2009, Schama presented a [[BBC Radio 4]] show entitled ''Baseball and Me'', both exploring the history of the game and describing his own personal support of the [[Boston Red Sox]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00hyjl4/episodes/guide|title=BBC Radio 4 Extra - Simon Schama - Baseball and Me - Episode guide|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Schama presented a series of ten talks for the [[BBC Radio 4]] series ''A Point of View'':\n* ''Why We Like Tough Guys in Politics'': When times are hard people seem to prefer tough leaders.\n* ''Singing in the Rain'': Schama looks forward to spring with personal reflections on the changing seasons.\n* ''At the Heart of the Matter'': The politics surrounding President [[Barack Obama]]'s healthcare reforms.\n* ''The Gift of the Gab'': The history of political rhetoric and the power during election campaigns of televised debates.\n* ''Behold, Newstralia!'': Celebrates the distinctive history and culture of [[New Zealand]] and regrets any renewed talk of joining forces with Australia.\n* ''A Welcome Slice of American Pie'': Reflection on the quality of American food and eating habits.\n* ''The Drama of Politics'': The timeless drama of [[British politics]].\n* ''When Money is Just an Illusion'': Reflection on the meaning of money as represented by coins and notes and in art.\n* ''Hearts of Oak'': Reflection on the significance of one of the sights that will greet new MPs in the chamber of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] \u2013 the panelling made of solid oak.\n* ''Britain's New Politics'': Reflection on the [[2010 United Kingdom general election]], favourably comparing the British system for a swift handover of power to the cumbersome American one.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00rz0kn|title=A welcome slice of American pie, A Point of View - BBC Radio 4|website=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 the BBC commissioned Simon Schama to write and present a five-part series called ''A History of the Jews'' for [[BBC Two]] for transmission in 2012,<ref name=\"BBC AHOTJ 1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2011/02_february/24/schama.shtml|title=Simon Schama to present The History of the Jews on BBC Two|publisher=BBC|date=2 February 2011}}</ref> The title became ''[[The Story of the Jews]]'' and broadcast was delayed until September 2013.<ref name=\"BBC progs 2013 1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0392pzx|title=The Story of the Jews|work=[[BBC Programmes]]|publisher=BBC Two|accessdate=10 September 2013}}</ref> Writing in ''[[The Observer]]'', Andrew Anthony called it \"an astonishing achievement, a TV landmark.\"<ref name=\"Anthony\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2013/sep/28/observer-profile-simon-schama|title=Simon Schama: a man always making history|work=[[The Observer]]|date=28 September 2013|accessdate=7 October 2013|author=Anthony, Andrew}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Simon Schama wrote and presented five of the nine episodes of ''[[Civilisations (TV series)|Civilisations]]'', a reboot of the [[Civilisation (TV series)|1969 series]] by [[Kenneth Clark]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/GThNCvQtxsgJfJrxCxFJb2/civilisations-masterworks-of-beauty-and-ingenuity|title=Civilisations: Masterworks of beauty and ingenuity|website=BBC|access-date=16 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSchama is Jewish. He is married to Virginia Papaioannou, a geneticist from California; they have two children, Chloe and Gabriel.<ref name=\"telegraph the american future \">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/7912996/Simon-Schama-Could-I-have-multiple-personality-disorder.html|title=Simon Schama: Could I have multiple personality disorder?|publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=15 February 2017}}</ref> As of 2014, he resides in [[Briarcliff Manor, New York]].<ref name=\"Briarcliff\">{{cite news|last=Lombroso|first=Linda|title=Briarcliff historian tells PBS' 'The Story of the Jews'|url=http://www.lohud.com/story/entertainment/2014/03/24/story-jews-simon-schama/6835897/|accessdate=2 September 2014|newspaper=The Journal News|date=24 March 2014}}</ref> Schama is a [[Tottenham Hotspur]] supporter.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Schama |first1=Simon |title=The Yid Army\u2019s chants turn anti-semitism into kitsch banter |url=https://www.ft.com/content/c3fbd9e6-21e2-11e3-9b55-00144feab7de |website=Financial Times}}</ref>\n\n===Politics===\nIn 2010, Schama was a financial donor to [[Oona King]]'s unsuccessful campaign to become [[Mayor of London]].<ref name=\"guardian 2012 elections 1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/aug/13/labour-leadership-donations-miliband-burnham-balls|location=London|work=The Guardian|title=David Miliband hits it rich in leadership race as stars back Burnham and Balls|first=Michael|last=White|date=13 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2014, Schama was one of 200 public figures who were signatories to a letter to ''[[The Guardian]]'' expressing their hope that Scotland would vote to remain part of the United Kingdom in September's [[2014 Scottish independence referendum|referendum on that issue]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/aug/07/celebrities-open-letter-scotland-independence-full-text |title=Celebrities' open letter to Scotland \u2013 full text and list of signatories |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=7 August 2014 |accessdate=26 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, Schama joined [[Simon Sebag Montefiore]] and [[Howard Jacobson]] in writing a letter to ''[[The Times]]'' about their concern over [[Antisemitism in the UK Labour Party|antisemitism in the Labour Party]] under [[Jeremy Corbyn]]'s leadership, with particular reference to a growth in [[Anti-Zionism]] and its \"antisemitic characteristics\". Schama and Sebag Montefiore have both written historical works about Israel, while Jacobson has written regularly about Israel and the UK Jewish community in his newspaper columns.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/simon-schama-simon-sebag-montefiore-and-howard-jacobson-unite-to-condemn-labour-antisemitism-1.447432 |title=Schama, Sebag-Montefiore and Jacobson unite to condemn Labour antisemitism |work=The Jewish Chronicle | first=Daniel | last=Sugarman | date=6 November 2017 |accessdate=2 May 2018}}</ref> Schama made a further criticism of the party in July 2019, when he joined other leading Jewish figures in saying, in a letter to ''The Guardian'', that the crisis was \"a taint of international and historic shame\" and that trust in the party was \"fractured beyond repair\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jul/14/jewish-intellectuals-express-outrage-over-labours-handling-of-antisemitism-crisis |title=Jewish figures rail against Labour\u2019s handling of antisemitism charges |work=The Guardian | first=Stefan | last=Boscia | date=14 July 2019 |accessdate=24 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Israel====\nSchama was critical of a call by British novelist [[John Berger]] for an [[Academic boycott of Israel|academic boycott of Israel]] over its policies towards the [[Palestinians]]. Writing in ''[[The Guardian]]'' in an article co-authored with [[Anthony Julius]], Schama compared Berger's academic boycott to policies adopted by [[Nazi Germany]], saying: \"This is not the first boycott call directed at [[Jews]]. On 1 April 1933, only weeks after he came to power, [[Adolf Hitler|Hitler]] ordered a [[Nazi boycott of Jewish businesses| boycott of Jewish shops, banks, offices and department stores]].\"<ref name=\"guardian 2006 boycott 1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2006/dec/22/bergerboycott|title=John Berger is wrong|author1=Simon Schama|author2=Anthony Julius|publisher=The Guardian|date=22 December 2006|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 on the BBC, Schama debated with [[Vivienne Westwood]] the morality of Israel's actions in the [[2006 Lebanon War|Israel-Lebanon War]].<ref name=\"bbc2006\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/this_week/5210018.stm|title=This Week \u2013 Simon Schama & Vivienne Westwood|work=[[This Week (BBC TV series)|This Week]]|publisher=BBC|date=24 July 2006|accessdate=}}</ref> He described Israel's bombing of Lebanese city centres as unhelpful to Israel's attempt to \"get rid of\" Hezbollah.<ref name=\"bbc2006\"/> He said: \"Of course the spectacle and suffering makes us grieve. Who wouldn't grieve? But it's not enough to do that. We've got to understand. You've even got to understand Israel's point of view.\"<ref name=\"bbc2006\"/>\n\n====United States====\nSchama was a supporter of President [[Barack Obama]]<ref name=\"guardian obama support 1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/aug/30/barackobama.democrats20081|title=In its severity and fury, this was Obama at his most powerful and moving|last=Schama|first=Simon|date=30 August 2008|work=[[The Guardian]]|page=34|accessdate=5 November 2008|location=London}}</ref> and a critic of [[George W. Bush]].<ref name=\"guardian bush critic 1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/nov/03/george-bush-legacy-dubya|title=Nowhere man: a farewell to Dubya, all-time loser in presidential history|last=Schama|first=Simon|date=3 November 2008|work=[[The Guardian]]|pages=1\u20132|accessdate=5 November 2008|location=London}}</ref> He appeared on the BBC's coverage of the [[2008 United States presidential election|2008 US presidential election]], clashing with [[John R. Bolton|John Bolton]].<ref name=\"ET 2008 schama PE 1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/news/display.var.2465762.0.road_to_the_white_house.php |title=Road to the White House |date=5 November 2008 |work=[[The Evening Times]] |accessdate=5 November 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081108041640/http://www.eveningtimes.co.uk/news/display.var.2465762.0.road_to_the_white_house.php |archivedate=8 November 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Prizes and other honours==\n* 1977: [[Wolfson History Prize]], for ''Patriots and Liberators''\n* 1977: [[Leo Gershoy Award]], for ''Patriots and Liberators''\n* 1987: [[New York Times Best Books of the Year|''New York Times'' Best Books of the Year]], for ''The Embarrassment of Riches''\n* 1989: ''New York Times'' Best Books of the Year, for ''Citizens: A Chronicle of the French Revolution''\n* 1989: ''Yorkshire Post'' Book Award, for ''Citizens: A Chronicle of the French Revolution''\n* 1990: [[NCR Book Award]], for ''Citizens: A Chronicle of the French Revolution''\n* 1992: [[American Academy of Arts and Letters]] Award for Literature\n* 1995: Elected to Honorary Fellowship, Christ's College, Cambridge\n* 1996: Lionel Trilling Book Award, for ''Landscape and Memory''\n* 1996: [[National Magazine Awards]], for critical essays in [[The New Yorker]]\n* 1996: [[WH Smith Literary Award]], for ''Landscape and Memory''\n* 2001: [[St. Louis Literary Award]] from the [[Saint Louis University]] Library Associates<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slu.edu/libraries/associates/award.html|title=Saint Louis Literary Award - Saint Louis University|website=www.slu.edu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://lib.slu.edu/about/associates/literary-award/schama|title=Saint Louis University Library Associates Announce Winner of 2001 Literary Award|author=Saint Louis University Library Associates|accessdate=25 July 2016}}</ref>\n* 2001: Broadcasting Press Guild Writer's Award, for ''A History of Britain''\n* 2001: Nominated for BAFTA Huw Wheldon Award for Specialised Programme or Series (Arts, History, Religion and Science), for ''A History of Britain''<ref name=\"Wheldon\">{{cite web | url=http://awards.bafta.org/keyword-search?keywords=Huw+Wheldon+Award | title=BAFTA Awards | publisher=British Academy of Film and Television Arts | accessdate=12 November 2013}}</ref>\n* 2002: Nominated for BAFTA Richard Dimbleby Award for the Best Presenter (Factual, Features and News), for ''A History of Britain''\n* 2003: Nominated for Outstanding Individual Achievement in a Craft: Writing [[Emmy Award]] for ''The Two Winstons'', an episode of ''A History of Britain''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0769988/awards|title=Simon Schama - Awards|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n* 2006: [[National Book Critics Circle Award]] for Non-fiction winner, for ''Rough Crossings''<ref name=\"NYT 2006 NBCCA 1\">Bosman, Julie. \"National Briefing | Arts: National Book Critics Circle Winners\", ''New York Times'' (9 March 2007): 20. Academic Search Premier; accessed 1 May 2009.</ref>\n* 2006: Hessell-Tiltman Prize Shortlist, for ''Rough Crossings''\n* 2007: [[International Emmy Award]], for ''Bernini'', an episode of ''Simon Schama's Power of Art''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.columbia.edu/cu/news/07/11/schama.html|title=Professor Schama Wins International Emmy for Power of Art|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n* 2007: Nominated for BAFTA Huw Wheldon Award for Specialised Factual Programme or Series, for ''Simon Schama's Power of Art''\n* 2008: ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''{{'}}s 110 Best Books: The Perfect Library, for ''Citizens: A Chronicle of the French Revolution''\n* 2011: Kenyon Review Award for Literary Achievement<ref>{{cite web|title=Kenyon Review for Literary Achievement|url=https://www.kenyonreview.org/programs/kenyon-review-award-for-literary-achievement/simon-schama|website=kenyonreview.org|accessdate=16 June 2018}}</ref> \n* 2015: [[Corresponding Fellow of the British Academy|Corresponding Fellow]] of the [[British Academy]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britac.ac.uk/news/british-academy-fellowship-reaches-1000-42-new-uk-fellows-are-welcomed|title=British Academy Fellowship reaches 1,000 as 42 new UK Fellows are welcomed|date=16 July 2015|access-date=16 June 2018}}</ref>\n* 2015: [[Feltrinelli Prize]] for History\n* 2017: [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Literature]]<ref>Natasha Onwuemezi, [http://www.thebookseller.com/news/syal-and-mcdermid-named-new-rsl-fellows-564396 \"Rankin, McDermid and Levy named new RSL fellows\"], ''[[The Bookseller]]'', 7 June 2017; accessdate 16 June 2018.</ref>\n* [[2018 Birthday Honours|2018]]: [[Knight Bachelor]], for services to history\n\n==Bibliography==\n;Books\n* ''Patriots and Liberators: Revolution in the Netherlands 1780\u20131813'' (1977)\n* ''Two Rothschilds and the Land of Israel'' (1978)\n* ''[[The Embarrassment of Riches|The Embarrassment of Riches: An Interpretation of Dutch Culture in the Golden Age]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Citizens: A Chronicle of the French Revolution]]'' (1989)<ref name=\"snowman\"/>\n* ''Dead Certainties: Unwarranted Speculations'' 