ackground:#f2dfc6;\"| Song title\n!style=\"background:#f2dfc6;\"| Song type\n!style=\"background:#f2dfc6;\"| Lyrics\n!style=\"background:#f2dfc6;\"| Composer\n!style=\"background:#f2dfc6;\"| Performer\n!style=\"background:#f2dfc6;\"| Producer\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| The Extraordinary<br>\u683c\u5916\u7cbe\u5f69 \n|align=\"center\"| Opening theme song\n|align=\"center\"| \u738b\u632f\u58f0\n|align=\"center\"| \u5468\u4ee5\u529b\n|align=\"center\"| \u960e\u5955\u683c Janice Yan\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|&mdash;\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| Tears<br>\u501f\u4f60\u4e00\u70b9\u6cea\n|rowspan=3 align=\"center\"| Sub-theme song \n|align=\"center\"| \u59da\u82e5\u9f99\n|align=\"center\"| \u90d1\u6960\n|align=\"center\"| \u52a8\u529b\u706b\u8f66 [[Power Station (Taiwanese band)|Power Station]]\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| Wait For Love<br>\u7b49\u4e00\u7b49\u7231\u60c5\n|align=\"center\"| \u4e50\u58f0\n|align=\"center\"| \u9093\u78a7\u6e90\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"| \u7f57\u7f8e\u4eea [[Bonnie Loo]]\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"| \u9ea6\u5982\u4e3d\n|-\n|align=\"center\"| Watching Over You<br>\u5b88\u62a4\u4f60\n|align=\"center\"| \u9ad8\u98de\n|align=\"center\"| Benny Wong\n|}\n\n==Development==\n\nDakota Crescent is one of Singapore's earliest [[Housing and Development Board|(HDB)]] estates, built in 1958 by the [[Singapore Improvement Trust]] (SIT), which preceded the HDB. In July 2014, it was decided that the housing estate would be redeveloped under the HDB's [[Selective En bloc Redevelopment Scheme|SERS]] scheme and all residents would have to relocate by 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dakota Crescent tenants hit by news of redevelopment|url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/dakota-crescent-tenants-hit-news-redevelopment| access-date= 13 December 2016}}</ref> This prompted a campaign by activists for its conservation,<ref>{{cite news|title=\"Group pushing to save Dakota Crescent\"|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/group-pushing-to-save-dakota-crescent|accessdate=13 December 2016}}</ref> works of art to be created about it<ref>{{cite news|title=Community theatre show puts spotlight on Dakota Crescent and its residents|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/entertainment/community-theatre-show/2915036.html?cx_tag=similarcna&cid=tg:recos:similarcna:standard#cxrecs_s|accessdate=13 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Overwhelming response to Drama Box\u2019s site-specific performance in Dakota Crescent|url=http://www.todayonline.com/entertainment/arts/overwhelming-response-drama-boxs-site-specific-performance-dakota-crescent?cx_tag=similartd&cid=tg:recos:similartd:standard#cxrecs_s|accessdate=13 December 2016}}</ref> and also a spike in the amount of coverage given to Dakota Crescent by the media.<ref>{{cite news|title=5 things to remember about Dakota Crescent|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/5-things-to-remember-about-dakota-crescent|accessdate=13 December 2016}}</ref> Within weeks of the announcement by the HDB, Dakota Crescent drew considerable attention from many Singaporeans, amid which this drama series was produced.\n\nThis drama series was produced also as a means of kick-starting the commemoration of 35 years of Singapore-produced Chinese-language television in Singapore. As part of this, Mediacorp's famous Chinese-speaking comedy icons, such as ''[[Paris and Milan]]'' character Auntie Lucy (played by [[Dennis Chew]]) and Liang Po Po (played by [[Jack Neo]]) of ''Comedy Nite'', will be making cameo appearances in this drama.<ref>{{cite news|title=\"\u7eda\u8000\"\u5496\u5561\u9986\u6084\u6084\u5f00\u4e1a \u5218\u5b50\u7eda\u300a\u5927\u82f1\u96c4\u300b\u9996\u6b21\u6311\u6218\u641e\u7b11\u89d2\u8272|url=http://www.channel8news.sg/news8/lifestyle/entertainment/20160526-lif-jesseca/2819006.html?cid=ch8news-fb|publisher=Channel 8 News and Current Affairs|date=26 May 2016|accessdate=14 June 2016|language=Chinese}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=\u9648\u6cd3\u5b87\uff1a\u65b0\u5267\u89d2\u8272\u53d6\u540d\u81ea\"\u8fbe\u54e5\u6253\u5f2f\"\u611f\u8363\u5e78 \u62cd\u5b8c\u620f\u6025\u7740\u56de\u5bb6\u770b\u5b69\u5b50|url=http://www.channel8news.sg/news8/lifestyle/entertainment/20160526-lif-shaun/2820150.html|publisher=Channel 8 News and Current Affairs|date=26 May 2016|accessdate=14 June 2016|language=Chinese}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Auntie Lucy\u91cd\u51fa\u6c5f\u6e56 \u5ba2\u4e32\u91cd\u5934\u5267\u300a\u5927\u82f1\u96c4\u300b|url=http://www.channel8news.sg/news8/lifestyle/entertainment/20160527-lif-lucy/2820556.html|publisher=Channel 8 News and Current Affairs|date=27 May 2016|accessdate=14 June 2016|language=Chinese}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=\u9648\u6c49\u73ae\u633a\u810a\u67f1\u9aa8\u4f24\u53e3\u62cd\u620f \u4e3a\u6bcd\u4eb2\u7948\u798f\u6539\u5403\u7d20|url=http://www.channel8news.sg/news8/lifestyle/entertainment/20160527-lif-hanwei/2820558.html|publisher=Channel 8 News and Current Affairs|date=27 May 2016|accessdate=14 June 2016|language=Chinese}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=\u6881\u5a46\u5a46\u91cd\u51fa\u6c5f\u6e56 \u6881\u5fd7\u5f3a\u65b0\u7247\u62d2\u5f53\u5bfc\u6f14\uff1f|url=http://tv.toggle.sg/en/channel8/entnews/default-6388454|publisher=Toggle|date=11 June 2016|accessdate=14 June 2016|language=Chinese}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=\u90d1\u658c\u8f89\u8d74\u4e2d\u56fd\u6f14\u8499\u53e4\u5927\u6c57 \u9648\u6cd3\u5b87\u4e0e\u59bb\u5973\u5206\u623f\u7761|url=http://tv.toggle.sg/en/channel8/entnews/default-6403322#slideshow-1|publisher=Toggle|date=18 June 2016|language=Chinese}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Tammi Tan|title=No sugar mummies for Ian Fang|url=http://tv.toggle.sg/en/channel8/entnews/no-sugar-mummies-for-ian-fang-6457836#slideshow-1|publisher=Toggle|date=16 July 2016|accessdate=17 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=\u5218\u5b50\u7eda\u671b\u529e\u6d77\u6ee9\u5a5a\u793c \u90d1\u60e0\u7389\"\u5403\"\u5ae9\u8349\u65b9\u4f1f\u6770|url=http://tv.toggle.sg/zh/channel8/entnews/default-6458130#slideshow-1|publisher=Toggle|date=16 July 2016|language=Chinese}}</ref>\n\nImaging sessions were done in end-April and early-May 2016, while the first scene was shot on 23 May.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u5218\u5b50\u7eda\u5426\u8ba4\u4e0b\u4e2a\u6708\u7ed3\u5a5a \u9648\u6cd3\u5b87\u671b\u643a\u59bb\u5973\u62cd\u5e7f\u544a|url=http://tv.toggle.sg/zh/channel8/entnews/default-6316308#slideshow-1|publisher=Toggle|date=29 May 2016|accessdate=14 June 2016|language=Chinese}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=\u9648\u90a6\u92c6\u4e0b\u6708\u642c\u5bb6\u8fce\u63a5\u5c0f\u516c\u4e3b \u9ec4\u70af\u8000\u6652\u513f\u7834\u5bb6\u53d8\u4f20\u95fb|url=http://tv.toggle.sg/en/channel8/entnews/default-6347388#slideshow-1|publisher=Toggle|date=17 May 2016|accessdate=14 June 2016|language=Chinese}}</ref> On 30 July 2016, in the nineteenth season of ''The Sheng Siong Show'', it was also announced that [[Power Station (Taiwanese band)|Power Station]] will be performing the drama's ending theme. They were in Singapore to promote their \"Next Station\" world tour which will be held on 27 August.\n\nA post screening session was conducted at Dakota Crescent's Care and Friends Centre. The cast of Hero - [[Shaun Chen]], [[Jesseca Liu]], [[Chen Hanwei]], [[Bonnie Loo]], [[Paige Chua]], [[Ian Fang]], [[Sheila Sim (actress)|Sheila Sim]], [[Youyi (actress)|Youyi]], He Yingying, [[Aileen Tan]], [[Brandon Wong (actor)|Brandon Wong]] and [[Jin Yinji]] were present. The first episode of the show was also broadcast there.\n\n*The series consists of 30 episodes, and aired from 29 November 2016 to 9 January 2017.\n\n==Awards & Nominations==\n===[[Star Awards 2017]]===\nThe series has the most nominations in [[Star Awards 2017]], and won two, which was Best Supporting Actress and Drama Serial.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" - style=\"background:#FAEB86;\" align=\"center\" | [[Star Awards]] \u2013 Acting Awards\n|-\n! Accolades !! Category !! Nominees !! Result\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|The Road to Star Awards 2017 Episode 1<br> \u7ea2\u661f\u5927\u